ndian academic and political scientist\n*[[Zulkifli Hasan]] (born 1962), Indonesian politician\n\n==Fictional characters==\n*[[Dr. Lily Hassan]], character in the British soap opera ''Doctors''\n*[[Hassani (Sleeper Cell character)]], character in the American television series ''Sleeper Cell''\n*[[Omar Hassan (24 character)]], character in the American television series ''24''\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hazan (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Hassan (given name)]]\n*[[Hession (surname)]]\n*[[Hassoun]]\n*[[Irish name]]\n*[[Os\u00e1in]]\n*[[Hass (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Haas]]\n*[[De Haas]]\n*[[Lists of most common surnames]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{surname|Hassan}}\n\n[[Category:Surnames]]\n[[Category:Arabic-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Irish-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Gaelic-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Hebrew-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Jewish surnames]]\n[[Category:Mizrahic surnames]]\n[[Category:Sephardic surnames]]\n[[Category:Scottish surnames]]\n[[Category:Surnames of Arabic origin]]\n[[Category:Surnames of Irish origin]]\n[[Category:Surnames of Israeli origin]]\n[[Category:Surnames of Scottish origin]]\n\n\n[[bg:\u0425\u0430\u0441\u0430\u043d]]\n[[de:Hassan]]\n[[fr:Hassan]]\n[[nl:Hassan (achternaam)]]\n[[ja:\u30cf\u30b5\u30f3]]\n[[no:Hassan]]\n[[ru:\u0425\u0430\u0441\u0430\u043d (\u0438\u043c\u044f)]]\n", "name_user": "DavidSteirman", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hassan_(surname)"}
{"title_page": "List of military slang terms", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Globalize|date=November 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n[[Military slang]] is a colloquial language used by and associated with members of various [[military]] forces. This page lists slang words or phrases that originate with military forces, are used exclusively by military personnel or are strongly associated with military organizations.\n\n==Acronym slang==\nA number of military slang terms are [[Acronym and initialism|acronyms]]. These include ''SNAFU'', ''SUSFU'', ''FUBAR'' and similar terms used by various branches of the United States military during World War II.\n\n===BOHICA===\n''BOHICA'' (''Bend Over, Here It Comes Again'') is the title of a bestselling 1987 book by Scott T. Barnes. The book is the true account of a US ISA covert paramilitary operation, dubbed Operation Grand Eagle, that took place in Laos in 1981 with a small group of Green Berets, ISA operatives, and CIA staff. Later the operation would be the subject of several US Senate hearings, congressional hearings, and a Federal Grand Jury investigation.\n\n\"BOHICA\" was to be used as the code word on covert communications with the NSA/CIA and ISA HQ. During the mission, it was uncovered that criminals of war were still being held captive in Laos. Two were ordered assassinated and to date have never been rescued, as it was determined they may have been off-the-book CIA operatives smuggling drugs.\n\nThe ''Log,'' the humor magazine written by and for Midshipmen at the United States Naval Academy, featured a series of comics titled \"The Bohica Brothers,\" dating back to the early 1970s.\n\n===FUBAR===\n{{distinguish-otheruses2|Foobar|FUBAR}}\n{{Wiktionary|FUBAR}}\n\n''FUBAR'' (''Fucked/Fouled Up Beyond All Recognition/Any Repair/All Reason''), like SNAFU and SUSFU, dates from [[World War II]]. The ''Oxford English Dictionary'' lists ''Yank, the Army Weekly magazine'' (1944, 7 Jan. p.&nbsp;8) as its earliest citation: \"The FUBAR squadron. \u2025 FUBAR? It means 'Fucked/Fouled Up Beyond All Recognition.\"<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2005 |title =fubar, ''adj''. |encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |publisher=Oxford University Pres |location=Oxford}}</ref>\n\nAnother version of FUBAR, said to have originated in the military, gives its meaning as Fucked Up By Assholes in the Rear. This version has at least surface validity in that it is a common belief among enlisted men and women that most problems are created by the military brass (officers, especially those bearing the rank of General, from one to four stars). This version is also most likely to have had its origin in the Army, where the senior officers command from the rear, as opposed to the Navy, where it is not uncommon for Admirals to command a fleet from one of the ships at sea, and therefore susceptible to attacks and death by the enemy (though it is freely acknowledged that the higher level Admirals usually command from a land base). Ditto as to Air Force Generals, who do not fly and/or directly command airplanes or even Squadrons or Air Wings. FUBAR had a resurgence in the American lexicon after the term was used in two popular movies: [[Tango and Cash]] (1989) and [[Saving Private Ryan]] (1998).<ref>{{cite web |title=Which movie did FUBAR come from?(forums) |url=https://forums.anandtech.com/threads/which-movie-did-fubar-come-from.1643805/ |website=ananadtech.com |publisher=Anandtech |accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis particular FUBAR acronym survived WWII and for a time in the 70s, found its way into the lexicon of management consultants. Their use of the term,(though the word, \u201crear,\u201d is not normally used to describe the vantage point of senior corporate executives) may have come about as the result of their frequent conclusions that the cause of corporate problems (inefficiencies and ineffectiveness causing poor profitability or a negative bottom line) rested not with rank and file workers, but with executives, particularly senior executives - the equivalent of senior military officers. Therefore, FUBAR (Fucked Up By Assholes in the Rear) still applied well, even if in reality it should have been rendered as FUBAT (Fucked Up By Assholes at the Top).\n\n===FUBU===\n{{distinguish|FUBU}}\n''FUBU'' (''Fucked/fouled Up Beyond all Understanding'') was also used during World War II.\n\n===SNAFU===\n{{main|SNAFU}}\n''SNAFU'' is widely used to stand for the sarcastic expression ''Situation Normal: All Fucked Up'', as a well-known example of military acronym slang. However, the military acronym originally stood for \"Status Nominal: All Fucked Up.\" It is sometimes [[Expurgation|bowdlerized]] to ''all fouled up'' or similar.<ref>{{cite web|last=Neary|first=Lynn|title=Fifty Years of 'The Cat in the Hat'| publisher=[[NPR|National Public Radio]]|quote= 'Situation Normal&nbsp; ... All Fouled Up,' as the first SNAFU animated cartoon put it|url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=7651308|access-date=2008-01-08}}</ref> It means that the situation is bad, but that this is a normal state of affairs. It is typically used in a joking manner to describe something that is working as intended. The acronym is believed to have originated in the [[United States Marine Corps]] during [[World War II]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine used the term in their June 16, 1942, issue: \"Last week U.S. citizens knew that gasoline rationing and rubber requisitioning were snafu.\"<ref name=\"OED\" /> Most reference works, including the [[Random House Webster's Unabridged Dictionary]], supply an origin date of 1940\u20131944, generally attributing it to the [[United States Army]].\n\n[[Rick Atkinson]] ascribes the origin of SNAFU, [[#FUBAR|FUBAR]], and a bevy of other terms to cynical [[G.I. (military)|G.I.s]] ridiculing the Army's penchant for acronyms.<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Day of Battle: The War in Sicily and Italy, 1943\u20131944 |series=The Liberation Trilogy |first=Rick |last=Atkinson |year=2007 |publisher=Henry Holt |isbn=978-0-8050-6289-2 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/dayofbattlewarin00atki }}</ref>\n\n[[Private Snafu]] is the title character of a series of military instructional films, most of which were written by [[Dr. Seuss|Theodor \"Dr. Seuss\" Geisel]], [[P. D. Eastman|Philip D. Eastman]], and [[Munro Leaf]].<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1540-5931.2007.00404.x|title=Children's Literature Goes to War: Dr. Seuss, P. D. Eastman, Munro Leaf, and the Private SNAFU Films (1943?46)|journal=The Journal of Popular Culture|volume=40|issue=3|pages=468|year=2007|last1=Nel|first1=Philip}}</ref>\n\nIn modern usage, ''snafu'' is sometimes used as an [[interjection]], though it is mostly now used as a noun. ''Snafu'' also sometimes refers to a bad situation, mistake, or cause of the trouble. It is more commonly used in modern [[vernacular]] to describe running into an error or problem that is large and unexpected. For example, in 2005, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published an article titled \"Hospital Staff Cutback Blamed for Test Result Snafu\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Hospital Staff Cutback Blamed for Test Result Snafu |last=Santora |first=Marc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/19/nyregion/19pap.html?scp=4&sq=snafu&st=cse |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 19, 2005 |access-date=29 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe attribution of ''SNAFU'' to the American military is not universally accepted: it has also been attributed to the [[United Kingdom|British]],<ref>{{Cite book |title=Rawson's Dictionary of Euphemisms and Other Doubletalk: Being a Compilation of Linguistic Fig Leaves and Verbal Flourishes for Artful Users of the English Language |year=1995 |location=New York |publisher=Crown |first=Hugh |last=Rawson |isbn=978-0-517-70201-7}}</ref> although the Oxford English Dictionary gives its origin and first recorded use as the U.S. military.<ref name=\"OED\" />\n\nIn a wider study of military slang, Frederick Elkin noted in 1946 that there \"are a few acceptable substitutes, such as 'screw up' or 'mess up,' but these do not have the emphasis value of the obscene equivalent.\" He considered the expression ''SNAFU'' to be \"a caricature of Army direction. The soldier resignedly accepts his own less responsible position and expresses his cynicism at the inefficiency of Army authority.\" He also noted that \"the expression \u2026 is coming into general civilian use.\"<ref>{{Citation| last= Elkin| first= Frederick| date=March  1946|title= The Soldier's Language| journal= American Journal of Sociology| volume= 51| issue= 5 Human Behavior in Military Society| publisher= The University of Chicago Press| pages= 414\u2013422| jstor= 2771105}}</ref>\n\n===An Imperial FU===\n''An Imperial FU'' (''An Imperial Fuck Up'') was used during [[World War I]] by soldiers of the outlying [[British Empire]], e.g. Canada, Australia, New Zealand, the [[Union of South Africa]], Kenya, [[Tanganyika]], [[India]], in reference to odd/conflicting orders from [[United Kingdom|British authorities]]. Note that during World War I, the British Empire had an ''[[Imperial War Cabinet]]'', and the troops from Australia were called the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] (AIF), not to be confused with the [[American Expeditionary Forces|AEF]], the [[American Expeditionary Forces]] of WW I, or the [[Allied Expeditionary Force]] of WW II.\n\n===SUSFU===\n''SUSFU'' (S''ituation Unchanged: Still Fucked Up'') is closely related to ''SNAFU''.\n\n''SNAFU'' and ''SUSFU'' were first recorded in ''[[American Notes and Queries]]'' in their September 13, 1941, issue.<ref name=\"OED\">{{Cite book |title=A Supplement to the Oxford English Dictionary |editor=Burchfield, R.W. |volume=Volume IV Se-Z |year=1986 |location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon |isbn=978-0-19-861115-8}}</ref>\n\n===TARFU===\n''TARFU'' (''Totally And Royally Fucked Up'' or ''Things Are Really Fucked Up'') was also used during World War II.\n\nThe [[1944 in film|1944]] U.S. Army animated shorts ''[[Three Brothers (1944 film)|Three Brothers]]'' and ''Private Snafu Presents Seaman Tarfu In The Navy'' (both directed by [[Friz Freleng]]), feature the characters Private Snafu, Private Fubar, and Seaman Tarfu (with a [[cameo appearance|cameo]] by [[Bugs Bunny]]).<ref name=\"three\">{{cite web|publisher = [[Internet Archive]]|title = Private Snafu \u2013 Three Brothers (1944)|url = https://archive.org/details/PrivateSnafu-ThreeBrothers1944|accessdate = 2011-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\"snafu\">{{cite web|author =Pietro Shakarian|title =Situation Normal All Fucked Up:A History of Private Snafu|work =goldenagecartoons.com|url =http://looney.goldenagecartoons.com/miscelooneyous/snafu/|accessdate =2008-05-05|url-status =dead|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080512092007/http://looney.goldenagecartoons.com/miscelooneyous/snafu/|archivedate =2008-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of government and military acronyms]]\n* [[List of U.S. government and military acronyms]]\n** [[List of United States Marine Corps acronyms and expressions]]\n** [[List of U.S. Navy acronyms and expressions]]\n** [[List of U.S. Air Force acronyms and expressions]]\n* [[FUBAR (film)|''FUBAR'' (film)]], a 2002 [[mockumentary]] by [[Michael Dowse]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Colby |first=Elbridge |date=1943 |title=Army Talk: A Familiar Dictionary of Soldier Speech |url= |location= |publisher=Princeton University Press |page= |isbn= |author-link= |ASIN=B00725XTA4}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dickson |first=Paul |date=2014 |title=War Slang: American Fighting Words & Phrases Since the Civil War |url= |location= |publisher=Courier Corporation |page= |isbn=9780486797168 |author-link=Paul Dickson (writer)}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hakim|first=Joy|title=A History of Us: War, Peace and all that Jazz|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=1995| location=New York|isbn=0-19-509514-6}}\n* {{cite news|last=Jacobson|first=Gary|date=August 14, 1994|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|title=Humor best way to remove last of 'Bohicans' resistance|page=7H|accessdate=7 November 2008|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D4DDA7D891CC&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D}}\n* {{cite news|last=Stromberg|first=Rich|date=May 10, 2005|work=[[UWIRE]]|title=Grab your ankles and say BOHICA|accessdate=7 November 2008|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-108572048.html}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n\nBOHICA by Scott Barnes published 1987<ref>BOHICA Book, published 1987</ref>\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|SNAFU|FUBAR|BOHICA}}\n* [[:Wiktionary:Appendix:Glossary of military slang]]\n* [[:Wiktionary:Category:Military slang by language]]\n* [http://dictionary.com/browse/SNAFU Meaning of SNAFU on Dictionary.com]\n* [http://www.acronymfinder.com/af-query.asp?String=exact&Acronym=SNAFU&Find=Find Acronym Finder's SNAFU entry]\n* [http://www.acronymfinder.com/af-query.asp?String=exact&Acronym=FUBAR&Find=Find Acronym Finder's FUBAR entry]\n* [https://archive.org/details/CommandPerformance Command Performance] Episode 101 from 15 Jan 1944 ([https://archive.org/download/CommandPerformance/CP_44-01-15_ep101-Frances_Langford__Virginia_OBrien.mp3 MP3 6M]) includes a song about SNAFU by the [[Spike Jones]] band.\n* [http://www2.iath.virginia.edu/sixties/HTML_docs/Resources/Glossary/Sixties_Term_Gloss_K_P.html Glossary of Military Terms & Slang from the Vietnam War]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090323040108/http://www.snafu.com/Snafu/SnafuStory.html How the term SNAFU originated]\n* [https://archive.org/details/home_front Internet Archive: Private SNAFU \u2013 The Home Front (1943)] \u2013 This is one of 26 Private SNAFU cartoons made by the US Army Signal Corps to educate and boost the morale of the troops.\n* [http://catb.org/~esr/jargon/html/S/SNAFU-principle.html SNAFU Principle]\n* [http://www.the-snafu-special.com/ The SNAFU Special \u2013 Official website of the C-47 #43-15073]\n* [[World Wide Words]], [[Michael Quinion]], [http://www.worldwidewords.org/articles/asye.htm ''Acronyms for your Enjoyment''.]\n\n[[Category:Military slang and jargon]]\n[[Category:Profanity]]\n[[Category:Lists of government and military acronyms|Military slang]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Globalize|date=November 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n[[Military slang]] is a colloquial language used by and associated with members of various [[military]] forces. This page lists slang words or phrases that originate with military forces, are used exclusively by military personnel or are strongly associated with military organizations.\n\n==Acronym slang==\nA number of military slang terms are [[Acronym and initialism|acronyms]]. These include ''SNAFU'', ''SUSFU'', ''FUBAR'' and similar terms used by various branches of the United States military during World War II.\n\n===BOHICA===\n''BOHICA'' (''Bend Over, Here It Comes Again'') is the title of a bestselling 1987 book by Scott T. Barnes. The book is the true account of a US ISA covert paramilitary operation, dubbed Operation Grand Eagle, that took place in Laos in 1981 with a small group of Green Berets, ISA operatives, and CIA staff. Later the operation would be the subject of several US Senate hearings, congressional hearings, and a Federal Grand Jury investigation.\n\n\"BOHICA\" was to be used as the code word on covert communications with the NSA/CIA and ISA HQ. During the mission, it was uncovered that criminals of war were still being held captive in Laos. Two were ordered assassinated and to date have never been rescued, as it was determined they may have been off-the-book CIA operatives smuggling drugs.\n\nThe ''Log,'' the humor magazine written by and for Midshipmen at the United States Naval Academy, featured a series of comics titled \"The Bohica Brothers,\" dating back to the early 1970s.\n\n===FUBAR===\n{{distinguish-otheruses2|Foobar|FUBAR}}\n{{Wiktionary|FUBAR}}\n\n''FUBAR'' (''Fucked/Fouled Up Beyond All Recognition/Any Repair/All Reason''), like SNAFU and SUSFU, dates from [[World War II]]. The ''Oxford English Dictionary'' lists ''Yank, the Army Weekly magazine'' (1944, 7 Jan. p.&nbsp;8) as its earliest citation: \"The FUBAR squadron. \u2025 FUBAR? It means 'Fucked/Fouled Up Beyond All Recognition.\"<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2005 |title =fubar, ''adj''. |encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary |edition=third |publisher=Oxford University Pres |location=Oxford}}</ref>\n\nAnother version of FUBAR, said to have originated in the military, gives its meaning as Fucked Up By Assholes in the Rear. This version has at least surface validity in that it is a common belief among enlisted men and women that most problems are created by the military brass (officers, especially those bearing the rank of General, from one to four stars). This version is also most likely to have had its origin in the Army, where the senior officers command from the rear, as opposed to the Navy, where it is not uncommon for Admirals to command a fleet from one of the ships at sea, and therefore susceptible to attacks and death by the enemy (though it is freely acknowledged that the higher level Admirals usually command from a land base). Ditto as to Air Force Generals, who do not fly and/or directly command airplanes or even Squadrons or Air Wings. FUBAR had a resurgence in the American lexicon after the term was used in two popular movies: [[Tango and Cash]] (1989) and [[Saving Private Ryan]] (1998).<ref>{{cite web |title=Which movie did FUBAR come from?(forums) |url=https://forums.anandtech.com/threads/which-movie-did-fubar-come-from.1643805/ |website=ananadtech.com |publisher=Anandtech |accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis particular FUBAR acronym survived WWII and for a time in the 70s, found its way into the lexicon of management consultants. Their use of the term,(though the word, \u201crear,\u201d is not normally used to describe the vantage point of senior corporate executives) may have come about as the result of their frequent conclusions that the cause of corporate problems (inefficiencies and ineffectiveness causing poor profitability or a negative bottom line) rested not with rank and file workers, but with executives, particularly senior executives - the equivalent of senior military officers. Therefore, FUBAR (Fucked Up By Assholes in the Rear) still applied well, even if in reality it should have been rendered as FUBAT (Fucked Up By Assholes at the Top).\n\n===FUBU===\n{{distinguish|FUBU}}\n''FUBU'' (''Fucked/fouled Up Beyond all Understanding'') was also used during World War II.\n\n===SNAFU===\n{{main|SNAFU}}\n''SNAFU'' is widely used to stand for the sarcastic expression ''Situation Normal: All Fucked Up'', as a well-known example of military acronym slang. However, the military acronym originally stood for \"Status Nominal: All Fucked Up.\" It is sometimes [[Expurgation|bowdlerized]] to ''all fouled up'' or similar.<ref>{{cite web|last=Neary|first=Lynn|title=Fifty Years of 'The Cat in the Hat'| publisher=[[NPR|National Public Radio]]|quote= 'Situation Normal&nbsp; ... All Fouled Up,' as the first SNAFU animated cartoon put it|url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=7651308|access-date=2008-01-08}}</ref> It means that the situation is bad, but that this is a normal state of affairs. It is typically used in a joking manner to describe something that is working as intended. The acronym is believed to have originated in the [[United States Marine Corps]] during [[World War II]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine used the term in their June 16, 1942, issue: \"Last week U.S. citizens knew that gasoline rationing and rubber requisitioning were snafu.\"<ref name=\"OED\" /> Most reference works, including the [[Random House Webster's Unabridged Dictionary]], supply an origin date of 1940\u20131944, generally attributing it to the [[United States Army]].\n\n[[Rick Atkinson]] ascribes the origin of SNAFU, [[#FUBAR|FUBAR]], and a bevy of other terms to cynical [[G.I. (military)|G.I.s]] ridiculing the Army's penchant for acronyms.<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Day of Battle: The War in Sicily and Italy, 1943\u20131944 |series=The Liberation Trilogy |first=Rick |last=Atkinson |year=2007 |publisher=Henry Holt |isbn=978-0-8050-6289-2 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/dayofbattlewarin00atki }}</ref>\n\n[[Private Snafu]] is the title character of a series of military instructional films, most of which were written by [[Dr. Seuss|Theodor \"Dr. Seuss\" Geisel]], [[P. D. Eastman|Philip D. Eastman]], and [[Munro Leaf]].<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1540-5931.2007.00404.x|title=Children's Literature Goes to War: Dr. Seuss, P. D. Eastman, Munro Leaf, and the Private SNAFU Films (1943?46)|journal=The Journal of Popular Culture|volume=40|issue=3|pages=468|year=2007|last1=Nel|first1=Philip}}</ref>\n\nIn modern usage, ''snafu'' is sometimes used as an [[interjection]], though it is mostly now used as a noun. ''Snafu'' also sometimes refers to a bad situation, mistake, or cause of the trouble. It is more commonly used in modern [[vernacular]] to describe running into an error or problem that is large and unexpected. For example, in 2005, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published an article titled \"Hospital Staff Cutback Blamed for Test Result Snafu\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Hospital Staff Cutback Blamed for Test Result Snafu |last=Santora |first=Marc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/19/nyregion/19pap.html?scp=4&sq=snafu&st=cse |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 19, 2005 |access-date=29 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe attribution of ''SNAFU'' to the American military is not universally accepted: it has also been attributed to the [[United Kingdom|British]],<ref>{{Cite book |title=Rawson's Dictionary of Euphemisms and Other Doubletalk: Being a Compilation of Linguistic Fig Leaves and Verbal Flourishes for Artful Users of the English Language |year=1995 |location=New York |publisher=Crown |first=Hugh |last=Rawson |isbn=978-0-517-70201-7}}</ref> although the Oxford English Dictionary gives its origin and first recorded use as the U.S. military.<ref name=\"OED\" />\n\nIn a wider study of military slang, Frederick Elkin noted in 1946 that there \"are a few acceptable substitutes, such as 'screw up' or 'mess up,' but these do not have the emphasis value of the obscene equivalent.\" He considered the expression ''SNAFU'' to be \"a caricature of Army direction. The soldier resignedly accepts his own less responsible position and expresses his cynicism at the inefficiency of Army authority.\" He also noted that \"the expression \u2026 is coming into general civilian use.\"<ref>{{Citation| last= Elkin| first= Frederick| date=March  1946|title= The Soldier's Language| journal= American Journal of Sociology| volume= 51| issue= 5 Human Behavior in Military Society| publisher= The University of Chicago Press| pages= 414\u2013422| jstor= 2771105}}</ref>\n\n===An Imperial FU===\n''An Imperial FU'' (''An Imperial Fuck Up'') was used during [[World War I]] by soldiers of the outlying [[British Empire]], e.g. Canada, Australia, New Zealand, the [[Union of South Africa]], Kenya, [[Tanganyika]], [[India]], in reference to odd/conflicting orders from [[United Kingdom|British authorities]]. Note that during World War I, the British Empire had an ''[[Imperial War Cabinet]]'', and the troops from Australia were called the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] (AIF), not to be confused with the [[American Expeditionary Forces|AEF]], the [[American Expeditionary Forces]] of WW I, or the [[Allied Expeditionary Force]] of WW II.\n\n===SUSFU===\n''SUSFU'' (S''ituation Unchanged: Still Fucked Up'') is closely related to ''SNAFU''.\n\n''SNAFU'' and ''SUSFU'' were first recorded in ''[[American Notes and Queries]]'' in their September 13, 1941 issue.<ref name=\"OED\">{{Cite book |title=A Supplement to the Oxford English Dictionary |editor=Burchfield, R.W. |volume=Volume IV Se-Z |year=1986 |location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon |isbn=978-0-19-861115-8}}</ref>\n\n===TARFU===\n''TARFU'' (''Totally And Royally Fucked Up'' or ''Things Are Really Fucked Up'') was also used during World War II.\n\nThe [[1944 in film|1944]] U.S. Army animated shorts ''[[Three Brothers (1944 film)|Three Brothers]]'' and ''Private Snafu Presents Seaman Tarfu In The Navy'' (both directed by [[Friz Freleng]]), feature the characters Private Snafu, Private Fubar, and Seaman Tarfu (with a [[cameo appearance|cameo]] by [[Bugs Bunny]]).<ref name=\"three\">{{cite web|publisher = [[Internet Archive]]|title = Private Snafu \u2013 Three Brothers (1944)|url = https://archive.org/details/PrivateSnafu-ThreeBrothers1944|accessdate = 2011-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\"snafu\">{{cite web|author =Pietro Shakarian|title =Situation Normal All Fucked Up:A History of Private Snafu|work =goldenagecartoons.com|url =http://looney.goldenagecartoons.com/miscelooneyous/snafu/|accessdate =2008-05-05|url-status =dead|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080512092007/http://looney.goldenagecartoons.com/miscelooneyous/snafu/|archivedate =2008-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of government and military acronyms]]\n* [[List of U.S. government and military acronyms]]\n** [[List of United States Marine Corps acronyms and expressions]]\n** [[List of U.S. Navy acronyms and expressions]]\n** [[List of U.S. Air Force acronyms and expressions]]\n* [[FUBAR (film)|''FUBAR'' (film)]], a 2002 [[mockumentary]] by [[Michael Dowse]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Colby |first=Elbridge |date=1943 |title=Army Talk: A Familiar Dictionary of Soldier Speech |url= |location= |publisher=Princeton University Press |page= |isbn= |author-link= |ASIN=B00725XTA4}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dickson |first=Paul |date=2014 |title=War Slang: American Fighting Words & Phrases Since the Civil War |url= |location= |publisher=Courier Corporation |page= |isbn=9780486797168 |author-link=Paul Dickson (writer)}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hakim|first=Joy|title=A History of Us: War, Peace and all that Jazz|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=1995| location=New York|isbn=0-19-509514-6}}\n* {{cite news|last=Jacobson|first=Gary|date=August 14, 1994|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|title=Humor best way to remove last of 'Bohicans' resistance|page=7H|accessdate=7 November 2008|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D4DDA7D891CC&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D}}\n* {{cite news|last=Stromberg|first=Rich|date=May 10, 2005|work=[[UWIRE]]|title=Grab your ankles and say BOHICA|accessdate=7 November 2008|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-108572048.html}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n\nBOHICA by Scott Barnes published 1987<ref>BOHICA Book, published 1987</ref>\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|SNAFU|FUBAR|BOHICA}}\n* [[:Wiktionary:Appendix:Glossary of military slang]]\n* [[:Wiktionary:Category:Military slang by language]]\n* [http://dictionary.com/browse/SNAFU Meaning of SNAFU on Dictionary.com]\n* [http://www.acronymfinder.com/af-query.asp?String=exact&Acronym=SNAFU&Find=Find Acronym Finder's SNAFU entry]\n* [http://www.acronymfinder.com/af-query.asp?String=exact&Acronym=FUBAR&Find=Find Acronym Finder's FUBAR entry]\n* [https://archive.org/details/CommandPerformance Command Performance] Episode 101 from 15 Jan 1944 ([https://archive.org/download/CommandPerformance/CP_44-01-15_ep101-Frances_Langford__Virginia_OBrien.mp3 MP3 6M]) includes a song about SNAFU by the [[Spike Jones]] band.\n* [http://www2.iath.virginia.edu/sixties/HTML_docs/Resources/Glossary/Sixties_Term_Gloss_K_P.html Glossary of Military Terms & Slang from the Vietnam War]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090323040108/http://www.snafu.com/Snafu/SnafuStory.html How the term SNAFU originated]\n* [https://archive.org/details/home_front Internet Archive: Private SNAFU \u2013 The Home Front (1943)] \u2013 This is one of 26 Private SNAFU cartoons made by the US Army Signal Corps to educate and boost the morale of the troops.\n* [http://catb.org/~esr/jargon/html/S/SNAFU-principle.html SNAFU Principle]\n* [http://www.the-snafu-special.com/ The SNAFU Special \u2013 Official website of the C-47 #43-15073]\n* [[World Wide Words]], [[Michael Quinion]], [http://www.worldwidewords.org/articles/asye.htm ''Acronyms for your Enjoyment''.]\n\n[[Category:Military slang and jargon]]\n[[Category:Profanity]]\n[[Category:Lists of government and military acronyms|Military slang]]\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200etop:added short description)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_military_slang_terms"}
{"title_page": "R\u0103stoli\u021ba", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2008}}\n{{for|the river in Mure\u0219 County|R\u0103stoli\u021ba (river)}}\n{{Redirect|Borzia|the cyanobacterium genus|Borzia (cyanobacteria)}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Mure\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map              = Rastolita jud Mures.png\n|map_caption            = Location in Mure\u0219 County\n|name=R\u0103stoli\u021ba\n|image_skyline = Galaoaia1.JPG\n|image_caption = \"Troi\u021ba\" (Holy Trinity) in G\u0103l\u0103oaia\n|area_total_km2=265.98\n|coordinates = {{coord|46|59|N|25|2|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n\n'''R\u0103stoli\u021ba''' ({{lang-hu|Ratosnya}}, <small>Hungarian pronunciation:</small> {{convertIPA-hu|'|r|a|t|o|s|ny|a}}) is a commune in [[Mure\u0219 County]], [[Transylvania]], [[Romania]] that is composed of five villages: Andreneasa (''Andr\u00e1stelep''), Borzia (''Borzia''), G\u0103l\u0103oaia (''Galonya''), Iod (''J\u00f3d'') and R\u0103stoli\u021ba.\n\nIt has a population of 2,230: 82% [[Romanians]], 17% [[Hungarians]] and 1% [[Romani people|Romani]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Hungarian exonyms (Mure\u0219 County)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|R\u0103stoli\u021ba, Mure\u0219}}\n\n{{Mure\u0219 County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rastolita}}\n[[Category:Communes in Mure\u0219 County]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2008}}\n{{for|the river in Mure\u0219 County|R\u0103stoli\u021ba (river)}}\n{{Redirect|Borzia|the cyanobacterium genus|Borzia (cyanobacteria)}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Mure\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Mure\u0219 County\n|name=R\u0103stoli\u021ba\n|image_skyline = Galaoaia1.JPG\n|image_caption = \"Troi\u021ba\" (Holy Trinity) in G\u0103l\u0103oaia\n|area_total_km2=265.98\n|coordinates = {{coord|46|59|N|25|2|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n\n'''R\u0103stoli\u021ba''' ({{lang-hu|Ratosnya}}, <small>Hungarian pronunciation:</small> {{convertIPA-hu|'|r|a|t|o|s|ny|a}}) is a commune in [[Mure\u0219 County]], [[Transylvania]], [[Romania]] that is composed of five villages: Andreneasa (''Andr\u00e1stelep''), Borzia (''Borzia''), G\u0103l\u0103oaia (''Galonya''), Iod (''J\u00f3d'') and R\u0103stoli\u021ba.\n\nIt has a population of 2,230: 82% [[Romanians]], 17% [[Hungarians]] and 1% [[Romani people|Romani]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Hungarian exonyms (Mure\u0219 County)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|R\u0103stoli\u021ba, Mure\u0219}}\n\n{{Mure\u0219 County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rastolita}}\n[[Category:Communes in Mure\u0219 County]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R%C4%83stoli%C8%9Ba"}
{"title_page": "No\u00ebl Coward", "text_new": "{{short description|English playwright, composer, director, actor and singer}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{bots|deny=Citation bot}}\n<!--Please review the discussions at and preceding https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:No%C3%ABl_Coward/Archive_2#RfC:_Should_an_Infobox_be_added_to_the_page? before considering adding an infobox -->\n[[File:Noel Coward Allan warren edit 1.jpg|thumb|Coward in 1972]]\n\n'''Sir No\u00ebl Peirce<!--YES, it is spelled PEIRCE--> Coward''' (16 December 1899{{snd}}26 March 1973) was an English playwright, composer, director, actor and singer, known for his wit, flamboyance, and what ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine called \"a sense of personal style, a combination of cheek and chic, pose and poise\".<ref name=Time1969>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,941819-2,00.html \"Noel Coward at 70\",] ''Time'', 26 December 1969, accessed 2 May 2011</ref>\n\nCoward attended a dance academy in London as a child, making his professional stage d\u00e9but at the age of eleven. As a teenager he was introduced into the high society in which most of his plays would be set. Coward achieved enduring success as a playwright, publishing more than 50 plays from his teens onwards. Many of his works, such as ''[[Hay Fever (play)|Hay Fever]]'', ''[[Private Lives]]'', ''[[Design for Living]]'', ''[[Present Laughter]]'' and ''[[Blithe Spirit (play)|Blithe Spirit]]'', have remained in the regular theatre repertoire. He composed hundreds of songs, in addition to well over a dozen musical theatre works (including the operetta ''[[Bitter Sweet]]'' and comic [[revue]]s), screenplays, poetry, several volumes of short stories, the novel ''Pomp and Circumstance'', and a three-volume autobiography. Coward's stage and film acting and directing career spanned six decades, during which he starred in many of his own works.\n\nAt the outbreak of the Second World War Coward volunteered for war work, running the British propaganda office in Paris. He also worked with the Secret Service, seeking to use his influence to persuade the American public and government to help Britain. Coward won an [[Academy Honorary Award]] in 1943 for his naval film drama ''[[In Which We Serve]]'' and was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1969. In the 1950s he achieved fresh success as a cabaret performer, performing his own songs, such as \"[[Mad Dogs and Englishmen (song)|Mad Dogs and Englishmen]]\", \"[[London Pride (song)|London Pride]]\" and \"[[I Went to a Marvellous Party]]\".\n\nCoward's plays and songs achieved new popularity in the 1960s and 1970s, and his work and style continue to influence popular culture. He did not publicly acknowledge his homosexuality, but it was discussed candidly after his death by biographers including [[Graham Payn]], his long-time partner, and in Coward's diaries and letters, published posthumously. The former Albery Theatre (originally the New Theatre) in London was renamed the [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] in his honour in 2006.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early years ===\nCoward was born in 1899 in [[Teddington]], [[Middlesex]], a south-western suburb of London. His parents were Arthur Sabin Coward (1856{{ndash}}1937), a piano salesman, and Violet Agnes Coward (1863{{ndash}}1954), daughter of [[s:A Naval Biographical Dictionary/Veitch, Henry Gordon|Henry Gordon Veitch]], a captain and surveyor in the [[Royal Navy]].<ref>Morley (1974), p. 2</ref> Violet's cousin, Rachel Veitch, was mother of Field-Marshal [[Douglas Haig, 1st Earl Haig|Douglas Haig]].<ref>Hoare, p. 2</ref> No\u00ebl Coward was the second of their three sons, the eldest of whom had died in 1898 at the age of six.<ref>Morley (1974), p. 3</ref> Coward's father lacked ambition and industry, and family finances were often poor.<ref>Morley (1974), pp. 4, 8 and 67</ref> Coward was bitten by the performing bug early and appeared in amateur concerts by the age of seven. He attended the [[Chapel Royal]] Choir School as a young child. He had little formal schooling but was a voracious reader.<ref name=Kenrick1>[[John Kenrick (theatre writer)|Kenrick, John]]. [http://www.musicals101.com/noelbio.htm \"Noel Coward \u2013 Biographical Sketch\"], Coward 101 at ''Musicals 101: The Cyber Encyclopedia of Musical Theatre, TV and Film'', 2000, accessed 9 March 2009</ref>\n\nEncouraged by his ambitious mother, who sent him to a dance academy in London,<ref>Hoare, p. 19</ref> Coward's first professional engagement was in January 1911 as Prince Mussel in the children's play ''The Goldfish''.<ref>\"The Little Theatre\", ''The Times'', 28 January 1911, p. 12</ref> In ''Present Indicative'', his first volume of memoirs, Coward wrote:\n{{quote|One day{{space}}... a little advertisement appeared in the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''.... It stated that a talented boy of attractive appearance was required by a Miss Lila Field to appear in her production of an all-children fairy play: ''The Goldfish.'' This seemed to dispose of all argument. I was a talented boy, God knows, and, when washed and smarmed down a bit, passably attractive. There appeared to be no earthly reason why Miss Lila Field shouldn't jump at me, and we both believed that she would be a fool indeed to miss such a magnificent opportunity.<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), pp. 21\u201322</ref>}}\n\n[[File:coward Hawtrey 1911.jpg|left|thumb|Coward ''(left)'' with [[Lydia Bilbrook]] ''(centre)'' and [[Charles Hawtrey (actor born 1858)|Charles Hawtrey]], 1911]]\nThe leading actor-manager [[Charles Hawtrey (actor born 1858)|Charles Hawtrey]], whom the young Coward idolised and from whom he learned a great deal about the theatre, cast him in the children's play ''[[Where the Rainbow Ends]]''. Coward played in the piece in 1911 and 1912 at the [[Garrick Theatre]] in London's [[West End theatre|West End]].<ref>Hoare, pp. 23\u201326</ref><ref name=times1912>\"Garrick Theatre\", ''The Times'', 12 December 1912, p. 8</ref> In 1912 Coward also appeared at the [[Savoy Theatre]] in ''An Autumn Idyll'' (as a dancer in the ballet) and at the [[London Coliseum]] in ''A Little Fowl Play'', by Harold Owen, in which Hawtrey starred.<ref>\"The Savoy Theatre\", ''The Times'', 26 June 1912, p. 10; \"The Coliseum\", 29 October 1912, p. 8; and \"Varieties etc\", 18 November 1912, p. 1</ref> [[Italia Conti Academy|Italia Conti]] engaged Coward to appear at the [[Liverpool Playhouse|Liverpool Repertory Theatre]] in 1913, and in the same year he was cast as the [[Lost Boys (Peter Pan)|Lost Boy]] Slightly in ''[[Peter and Wendy|Peter Pan]]''.<ref>\"The Cult of Peter Pan\", ''The Times'', 24 December 1913, p. 8</ref> He reappeared in ''Peter Pan'' the following year, and in 1915 he was again in ''Where the Rainbow Ends''.<ref>\"Fairies at the Garrick\", ''The Times'', 28 December 1915, p. 10</ref> He worked with other child actors in this period, including [[Hermione Gingold]] (whose mother threatened to turn \"that naughty boy\" out);<ref>Castle, p. 12</ref> [[Fabia Drake]]; [[Esm\u00e9 Wynne-Tyson|Esm\u00e9 Wynne]], with whom he collaborated on his earliest plays; Alfred Willmore, later known as [[Miche\u00e1l Mac Liamm\u00f3ir]]; and [[Gertrude Lawrence]] who, Coward wrote in his memoirs, \"gave me an orange and told me a few mildly dirty stories, and I loved her from then onwards.\"<ref name=times1912 /><ref>Hoare, pp. 27, 30 and 51</ref><ref name=times1916>\"The Happy Family\", ''The Times'', 19 December 1916, p. 11</ref>\n\n[[File:Noel Coward in his teens.jpg|upright=.57|thumb|right|Coward in his early teens]]\nIn 1914, when Coward was fourteen, he became the prot\u00e9g\u00e9 and probably the lover of [[Philip Streatfeild]], a society painter.<ref>Hoare, pp. 33\u201334</ref> Streatfeild introduced him to Mrs Astley Cooper and her high society friends.{{#tag:ref|Evangeline Julia Marshall, an eccentric society hostess (1854\u20131944), married Clement Paston Astley Cooper, grandson of [[Astley Paston Cooper|Sir Astley Paston Cooper]], on 10 July 1877. She inherited Hambleton Hall from her brother Walter Marshall (d. 1899), and there she entertained rising talents in the artistic world, including Streatfeild, the conductor [[Malcolm Sargent]] and the writer [[C. K. Scott Moncrieff|Charles Scott Moncrieff]], as well as the young Coward.<ref>[[Simon Callow|Callow, Simon]]. [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/apr/19/theatre \"Englishman abroad\",] ''The Guardian'', 19 April 2006, accessed 8 February 2009; [http://thepeerage.com/p25203.htm#i252021 \"Evangeline Julia Marshall\"], The Peerage, accessed 8 February 2009; and [http://www.hambletonhall.com/?about+us/Victorian-Hotel-History \"History\"], Hambleton Hall website, accessed 8 February 2009</ref>|group= n}} Streatfeild died from [[tuberculosis]] in 1915, but Mrs Astley Cooper continued to encourage her late friend's prot\u00e9g\u00e9, who remained a frequent guest at her estate, [[Hambleton Hall]].<ref>Hoare, pp. 39\u201343</ref>\n\nCoward continued to perform during most of the First World War, appearing at the [[Prince of Wales Theatre]] in 1916 in ''The Happy Family''<ref name=times1916 /> and on tour with [[Amy Brandon Thomas]]'s company in ''[[Charley's Aunt]]''. In 1917, he appeared in ''The Saving Grace'', a comedy produced by Hawtrey. Coward recalled in his memoirs, \"My part was reasonably large and I was really quite good in it, owing to the kindness and care of Hawtrey's direction. He took endless trouble with me{{space}}... and taught me during those two short weeks many technical points of comedy acting which I use to this day.\"<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), p. 66</ref>\n\nIn 1918, Coward was conscripted into the [[Artists Rifles]] but was assessed as unfit for active service because of a tubercular tendency, and he was discharged on health grounds after nine months.<ref>Lesley, pp. 41\u201342</ref> That year he appeared in the [[D. W. Griffith]] film ''[[Hearts of the World]]'' in an uncredited role. He sold short stories to several magazines to help his family financially.<ref name=Kenrick1 /> He also began writing plays, collaborating on the first two (''Ida Collaborates'' (1917) and ''Women and Whisky'' (1918)) with his friend Esm\u00e9 Wynne.<ref>[http://www.noelcoward.net/html/plays.html \"Plays and Musicals\"], The Noel Coward Society, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> His first solo effort as a playwright was ''[[The Rat Trap]]'' (1918) which was eventually produced at the [[Everyman Cinema, Hampstead|Everyman Theatre]], [[Hampstead]], in October 1926.<ref>Thaxter, John. [http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/rattrap-rev.htm \"The Rat Trap\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061215220640/http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/rattrap-rev.htm |date=15 December 2006 }} , British Theatre Guide, 2006, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> During these years, he met Lorn McNaughtan,{{#tag:ref|Later known by her married name, Lorn Loraine.<ref>Hoare, p. 79</ref>|group= n}} who became his private secretary and served in that capacity for more than forty years, until her death.<ref name=Kenrick1 />\n\n=== Inter-war successes ===\nIn 1920, at the age of 20, Coward starred in his own play, the light comedy ''[[I'll Leave It to You]]''. After a three-week run in [[Manchester]] it opened in London at the New Theatre (renamed the [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] in 2006), his first full-length play in the West End.<ref name=Thaxter>Thaxter, John. [http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/illleave-rev.htm ''I'll Leave It To You''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610013510/http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/illleave-rev.htm |date=10 June 2011 }} , British Theatre Guide, 2009</ref> [[Neville Cardus]]'s praise in ''[[The Guardian|The Manchester Guardian]]'' was grudging.<ref>Cardus, Neville. \"Gaiety Theatre\", ''[[The Manchester Guardian]]'', 4 May 1920, p. 13</ref> Notices for the London production were mixed, but encouraging.<ref name=Kenrick1 /> ''[[The Observer]]'' commented, \"Mr Coward... has a sense of comedy, and if he can overcome a tendency to smartness, he will probably produce a good play one of these days.\"<ref>Ervine, St John. \"At the Play\", ''The Observer'', 25 July 1920, p. 9</ref> ''The Times'', on the other hand, was enthusiastic: \"It is a remarkable piece of work from so young a head \u2013 spontaneous, light, and always 'brainy'.\"<ref>\"I'll Leave It to You\", ''The Times'', 22 July 1920, p. 10</ref>\n\n[[File:Coward pestle.jpg|left|thumb|upright=.57|Coward in ''[[The Knight of the Burning Pestle]]'' in 1920]]\nThe play ran for a month (and was Coward's first play seen in America),<ref name=Thaxter /> after which Coward returned to acting in works by other writers, starring as Ralph in ''[[The Knight of the Burning Pestle]]'' in [[Birmingham Repertory Theatre|Birmingham]] and then London.<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), pp. 104\u201305 and 112</ref> He did not enjoy the role, finding [[Francis Beaumont]] and his sometime collaborator [[John Fletcher (playwright)|John Fletcher]] \"two of the dullest Elizabethan writers ever known&nbsp;... I had a very, very long part, but I was very, very bad at it\".<ref>Castle, p. 38</ref> Nevertheless, ''The Manchester Guardian'' thought that Coward got the best out of the role,<ref>\"The Knight of the Burning Pestle\", ''The Manchester Guardian'', 25 November 1920, p. 14</ref> and ''The Times'' called the play \"the jolliest thing in London\".<ref>\"A Jacobean Romp\", ''The Times'', 25 November 1920, p. 10</ref>\n\nCoward completed a one-act satire, ''The Better Half'', about a man's relationship with two women. It had a short run at The Little Theatre, London, in 1922. The critic [[St. John Greer Ervine|St John Ervine]] wrote of the piece, \"When Mr Coward has learned that tea-table chitter-chatter had better remain the prerogative of women he will write more interesting plays than he now seems likely to write.\"<ref>Ervine, St John. \"New Grand Guignol Series\", ''The Observer'', 4 June 1922, p. 9</ref> The play was thought to be lost until a typescript was found in 2007 in the archive of the [[Lord Chamberlain's Office]], the official censor of stage plays in the UK until 1968.<ref>Thorpe, Vanessa. [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/sep/16/theatrenews.books \"Coward's long-lost satire was almost too 'daring' about women\",] ''The Observer'', 16 September 2007, accessed 22 September 2016</ref>\n\nIn 1921, Coward made his first trip to America, hoping to interest producers there in his plays. Although he had little luck, he found the Broadway theatre stimulating.<ref name=Kenrick1 /> He absorbed its smartness and pace into his own work, which brought him his first real success as a playwright with ''The Young Idea''. The play opened in London in 1923, after a provincial tour, with Coward in one of the leading roles.<ref>Hoare, pp. 89\u201391</ref> The reviews were good: \"Mr No\u00ebl Coward calls his brilliant little farce a 'comedy of youth', and so it is. And youth pervaded the Savoy last night, applauding everything so boisterously that you felt, not without exhilaration, that you were in the midst of a 'rag'.\"<ref>\"New Play at the Savoy\", ''The Times'', 2 February 1923, p. 8</ref> One critic, who noted the influence of [[George Bernard Shaw|Bernard Shaw]] on Coward's writing, thought more highly of the play than of Coward's newly found fans: \"I was unfortunately wedged in the centre of a group of his more exuberant friends who greeted each of his sallies with 'That's a No\u00eblism!'\"<ref>\"The Young Idea\", ''The Observer'', 4 February 1923, p. 11</ref>{{#tag:ref|Coward himself acknowledged that Shaw's ''[[You Never Can Tell (play)|You Never Can Tell]]'' was the primary inspiration for ''The Young Idea''.<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), p. 114</ref>|group= n}} The play ran in London from 1 February to 24 March 1923, after which Coward turned to [[revue]], co-writing and performing in [[Andr\u00e9 Charlot]]'s ''[[London Calling!]]''<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), pp. 112 and 150</ref>\n\n[[File:Lilian Braithwaite & No\u00ebl Coward.jpg|right|thumb|Coward with [[Lilian Braithwaite]], his co-star in ''[[The Vortex]]'' and the mother of his close friend [[Joyce Carey]]]]\nIn 1924, Coward achieved his first great critical and financial success as a playwright with ''[[The Vortex]].'' The story is about a nymphomaniac socialite and her cocaine-addicted son (played by Coward). Some saw the drugs as a mask for homosexuality;<ref>Hoare, p. 129</ref> [[Kenneth Tynan]] later described it as \"a [[jeremiad]] against narcotics with dialogue that sounds today not so much stilted as high-heeled\".<ref name=tynan>Tynan, pp. 286\u201388</ref> ''The Vortex'' was considered shocking in its day for its depiction of sexual vanity and drug abuse among the upper classes. Its notoriety and fiery performances attracted large audiences, justifying a move from a small suburban theatre to a larger one in the West End.<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), pp. 182\u201385</ref> Coward, still having trouble finding producers, raised the money to produce the play himself. During the run of ''The Vortex'', Coward met [[John C. Wilson|Jack Wilson]], an American stockbroker (later a director and producer), who became his business manager and lover. Wilson used his position to steal from Coward, but the playwright was in love and accepted both the larceny and Wilson's heavy drinking.<ref name=Kenrick2>Kenrick, John. [http://www.musicals101.com/noelbio2.htm \"Noel Coward \u2013 Biographical Sketch \u2013 Part II\"], Coward 101 at ''Musicals 101: The Cyber Encyclopedia of Musical Theatre, TV and Film'', 2000, accessed 9 March 2009</ref>\n\nThe success of ''The Vortex'' in both London and America caused a great demand for new Coward plays. In 1925 he premiered ''[[Fallen Angels (play)|Fallen Angels]]'', a three-act comedy that amused and shocked audiences with the spectacle of two middle-aged women slowly getting drunk while awaiting the arrival of their mutual lover.<ref>\"Fallen Angels\", ''The Manchester Guardian'', 23 April 1925, p. 12</ref> ''[[Hay Fever (play)|Hay Fever]]'', the first of Coward's plays to gain an enduring place in the mainstream theatrical repertoire, also appeared in 1925. It is a comedy about four egocentric members of an artistic family who casually invite acquaintances to their country house for the weekend and bemuse and enrage each other's guests. Some writers have seen elements of Coward's old mentor, Mrs Astley Cooper, and her set in the characters of the family.<ref>Hoare, pp. 42\u201343</ref> By the 1970s the play was recognised as a classic, described in ''The Times'' as a \"dazzling achievement; like ''[[The Importance of Being Earnest]]'', it is pure comedy with no mission but to delight, and it depends purely on the interplay of characters, not on elaborate comic machinery.\"<ref name=timesobit /> By June 1925 Coward had four shows running in the West End: ''The Vortex'', ''Fallen Angels'', ''Hay Fever'' and ''[[On with the Dance (musical)|On with the Dance]]''.<ref>Morley (1974), p. 107</ref> Coward was turning out numerous plays and acting in his own works and others'. Soon, his frantic pace caught up with him, and he collapsed on stage in 1926 while starring in a stage adaptation of ''[[The Constant Nymph (novel)|The Constant Nymph]]'' and had to take an extended rest, recuperating in [[Hawaii]].<ref name=Kenrick2 />\n\nOther Coward works produced in the mid-to-late 1920s included the plays ''[[Easy Virtue (play)|Easy Virtue]]'' (1926), a drama about a divorc\u00e9e's clash with her snobbish in-laws; ''[[The Queen Was in the Parlour]]'', a [[Ruritanian romance]]; ''[[This Was a Man]]'' (1926), a comedy about adulterous aristocrats; ''[[The Marquise]]'' (1927), an eighteenth-century costume drama; ''[[Home Chat (play)|Home Chat]]'' (1927), a comedy about a married woman's fidelity; and the revues ''On with the Dance'' (1925) and ''[[This Year of Grace]]'' (1928). None of these shows has entered the regular repertoire, but the last introduced one of Coward's best-known songs, \"A Room with a View\".<ref name=ncsongs>[http://www.noelcowardmusic.com/ncmi/appendices/appendix3.html \"Appendix 3 (The Relative Popularity of Coward's Works)\"], No\u00ebl Coward Music Index, accessed 29 November 2015</ref> His biggest failure in this period was the play ''[[Sirocco (play)|Sirocco]]'' (1927), which concerns free love among the wealthy. It starred [[Ivor Novello]], of whom Coward said, \"the two most beautiful things in the world are Ivor's profile and my mind\".<ref>Richards, p. 56</ref> Theatregoers hated the play, showing violent disapproval at the curtain calls and spitting at Coward as he left the theatre.<ref name=Kenrick2 /> Coward later said of this flop, \"My first instinct was to leave England immediately, but this seemed too craven a move, and also too gratifying to my enemies, whose numbers had by then swollen in our minds to practically the entire population of the British Isles.\"<ref>Richards, p. 26</ref>\n\nBy 1929 Coward was one of the world's highest-earning writers, with an annual income of \u00a350,000, more than \u00a32,800,000 in terms of 2018 values.<ref>[http://www.measuringworth.com/ppoweruk/ \"Purchasing Power of British Pounds from 1270 to the present\"], Measuring Worth website, accessed 6 June 2019</ref> Coward thrived during the [[Great Depression]], writing a succession of popular hits.<ref name=lahr93>Lahr, p. 93</ref> They ranged from large-scale spectaculars to intimate comedies. Examples of the former were the [[operetta]] ''[[Bitter Sweet]]'' (1929), about a woman who elopes with her music teacher,<ref name=C&N>Norton, Richard C. [http://operetta-research-center.org/coward-novello/ \"Coward & Novello\"], Operetta Research Center, 1 September 2007, accessed 29 November 2015</ref> and the historical extravaganza ''[[Cavalcade (play)|Cavalcade]]'' (1931) at [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]], about thirty years in the lives of two families, which required a huge cast, gargantuan sets and a complex hydraulic stage. Its [[Cavalcade (1933 film)|1933 film adaptation]] won the [[Academy Award]] for best picture.<ref>[http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1386188010849 \"Best Picture \u2013 1932/33 (6th)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221152803/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1386188010849 |date=21 February 2014 }}  Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, accessed 4 December 2013</ref> Coward's intimate-scale hits of the period included ''[[Private Lives]]'' (1930) and ''[[Design for Living]]'' (1932). In ''Private Lives'', Coward starred alongside his most famous stage partner, Gertrude Lawrence, together with the young [[Laurence Olivier]]. It was a highlight of both Coward's and Lawrence's career, selling out in both London and New York. Coward disliked long runs, and after this he made a rule of starring in a play for no more than three months at any venue.<ref name=Kenrick2 /> ''Design for Living'', written for [[Alfred Lunt]] and [[Lynn Fontanne]], was so risqu\u00e9, with its theme of bisexuality and a ''m\u00e9nage \u00e0 trois'', that Coward premiered it in New York, knowing that it would not survive the censor in London.<ref>Hoare, p. 249</ref>\n\n[[File:Novello-lunt-fontanne-campbell.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ivor Novello]], ''top l''., [[Alfred Lunt]], ''top r''., [[Lynn Fontanne]], ''lower l''. and [[Judy Campbell]]{{snd}}stars of Coward premi\u00e8res of the 1920s{{ndash}}1940s]]\nIn 1933 Coward wrote, directed and co-starred with the French singer [[Yvonne Printemps]] in both London and New York productions of an operetta, ''[[Conversation Piece (musical)|Conversation Piece]]'' (1933).<ref name=Kenrick2 /> He next wrote, directed and co-starred with Lawrence in ''[[Tonight at 8.30]]'' (1936), a cycle of ten short plays, presented in various permutations across three evenings.{{#tag:ref|The cycle effectively comprised only nine plays: although Coward wrote ten works for the cycle, ''[[Star Chamber (play)|Star Chamber]]'' was dropped after a single performance.<ref>Hoare, pp. 268\u201370</ref>|group= n}} One of these plays, ''[[Still Life (play)|Still Life]]'', was expanded into the 1945 [[David Lean]] film ''[[Brief Encounter]]''.<ref>Morley (1974), pp. 226\u201328 and 230</ref> ''Tonight at 8.30'' was followed by a musical, ''[[Operette (musical)|Operette]]'' (1938), from which the most famous number is \"The Stately Homes of England\", and a revue entitled ''[[Set to Music]]'' (1938, a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] version of his 1932 London revue, ''Words and Music'').<ref>Morley (1974), pp. 237 and 239</ref> Coward's last pre-war plays were ''[[This Happy Breed]]'', a drama about a working-class family, and ''[[Present Laughter]]'', a comic self-caricature with an egomaniac actor as the central character. These were first performed in 1942, although they were both written in 1939.<ref>Lahr, pp. 32 and 93</ref>\n\nBetween 1929 and 1936 Coward recorded many of his best-known songs for [[The Gramophone Company|His Master's Voice]] (HMV), now reissued on CD, including the romantic \"[[I'll See You Again]]\" from ''Bitter Sweet'', the comic \"[[Mad Dogs and Englishmen (song)|Mad Dogs and Englishmen]]\" from ''Words and Music'', and \"Mrs Worthington\".<ref>Naxos CDs 8.120559 and 8.120623</ref>\n\n=== Second World War ===\nWith the outbreak of the Second World War Coward abandoned the theatre and sought official war work. After running the British propaganda office in Paris, where he concluded that \"if the policy of His Majesty's Government is to bore the Germans to death I don't think we have time\",<ref>Richards, p. 105</ref> he worked on behalf of British intelligence.<ref>Koch, Stephen. [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/13/books/review/Koch-t.html \"The Playboy was a Spy\"], ''The New York Times'', 13 April 2008, accessed 4 January 2009</ref> His task was to use his celebrity to influence American public and political opinion in favour of helping Britain.{{#tag:ref|[[Harold Nicolson]], speaking for the Ministry of Information, stated that Coward \"possesses contacts with certain sections of opinion which are very difficult to reach through ordinary sources\".<ref>Lesley, p. 215</ref>|group= n}} He was frustrated by British press criticism of his foreign travel while his countrymen suffered at home, but he was unable to reveal that he was acting on behalf of the Secret Service.<ref name=hastings>Hastings, Chris. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1568190/Winston-Churchill-vetoed-Coward-knighthood.html \"Winston Churchill vetoed Coward knighthood\"], Telegraph.co.uk, 3 November 2007, accessed 4 January 2009</ref> In 1942 [[George VI]] wished to award Coward a knighthood for his efforts, but was dissuaded by [[Winston Churchill]]. Mindful of the public view of Coward's flamboyant lifestyle, Churchill used, as his reason for withholding the honour, Coward's \u00a3200 fine for contravening currency regulations in 1941.<ref name=hastings />\n\nHad the Germans invaded Britain, Coward was scheduled to be arrested and killed, as he was in [[The Black Book]] along with other figures such as [[Virginia Woolf]], [[Paul Robeson]], [[Bertrand Russell]], [[C. P. Snow]] and [[H. G. Wells]]. When this came to light after the war, Coward wrote: \"If anyone had told me at that time I was high up on the [[Nazi]] blacklist, I should have laughed&nbsp;... I remember [[Rebecca West]], who was one of the many who shared the honour with me, sent me a telegram which read: 'My dear \u2013 the people we should have been seen dead with'.\"<ref>Coward (''Future Indefinite''), p. 121</ref>\n\n[[File:Noel Coward Entertains the Men of the Eastern Fleet, HMS Victorious, Trincomalee, Ceylon, 1 August 1944 A25390.jpg|thumb|left|Coward, with [[Norman Hackforth]] at the piano, performing for sailors aboard {{HMS|Victorious|R38|6}} in Ceylon, August 1944]]\nChurchill's view was that Coward would do more for the war effort by entertaining the troops and the home front than by intelligence work: \"Go and sing to them when the guns are firing \u2013 that's your job!\"<ref>Morley (1974), p. 246</ref> Coward, though disappointed, followed this advice. He toured, acted and sang indefatigably in Europe, Africa, Asia and America.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,857528-1,00.html \"Light Entertainment\",] ''Time'', 19 July 1954, accessed 4 January 2009</ref> He wrote and recorded war-themed popular songs, including \"[[London Pride (song)|London Pride]]\" and \"[[Don't Let's Be Beastly to the Germans]]\". His London home was wrecked by German bombs in 1941, and he took up temporary residence at the [[Savoy Hotel]].<ref>Hoare, p. 317</ref> During one air raid on the area around the Savoy he joined [[Carroll Gibbons]] and [[Judy Campbell]] in impromptu cabaret to distract the captive guests from their fears.<ref>Hoare, p. 318</ref> Another of Coward's wartime projects, as writer, star, composer and co-director (alongside David Lean), was the naval film drama ''[[In Which We Serve]]''. The film was popular on both sides of the Atlantic, and he was awarded an [[Academy Honorary Award|honorary certificate of merit]] at the [[15th Academy Awards|1943 Academy Awards]] ceremony.<ref>[http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1386189663593 \"In Which we Serve\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20131205161150/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1386189663593 |date=5 December 2013 }} , Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, accessed 5 December 2013</ref> Coward played a naval captain, basing the character on his friend [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Lord Louis Mountbatten]]. Lean went on to direct and adapt film versions of several Coward plays.<ref name=Kenrick2 />\n\nCoward's most enduring work from the war years was the hugely successful black comedy ''[[Blithe Spirit (play)|Blithe Spirit]]'' (1941), about a novelist who researches the [[occult]] and hires a medium. A s\u00e9ance brings back the ghost of his first wife, causing havoc for the novelist and his second wife.<ref name=Kenrick2 /> With 1,997 consecutive performances, it broke box-office records for the run of a West End comedy, and was also produced on Broadway, where its original run was 650 performances.{{#tag:ref|The record (1,466 performances) had been held by ''[[Charley's Aunt]]'' since the 1890s.<ref>Gaye, p. 1525</ref> ''Blithe Spirit's'' West End record was overtaken by ''[[Boeing Boeing (play)|Boeing Boeing]]'' in the 1960s.<ref>Herbert, p. 1280</ref> The play was adapted into a [[Blithe Spirit (1945 film)|1945 film]], directed by Lean. Coward toured during 1942 in ''Blithe Spirit'', alternating the piece with his comedy ''Present Laughter'' and his working-class drama ''This Happy Breed''.<ref>Hoare, p. 331</ref>\n\nIn his ''Middle East Diary'' Coward made several statements that offended many Americans. In particular, he commented that he was \"less impressed by some of the mournful little [[Brooklyn]] boys lying there in tears amid the alien corn with nothing worse than a bullet wound in the leg or a fractured arm\".<ref>Calder, Robert. [https://books.google.com/books?id=HcpChZmn9s4C&pg=PA103&lpg=PA103#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Beware the British serpent''], p. 103</ref><ref>Hoare, p. 341</ref> After protests from both ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Washington Post]]'', the Foreign Office urged Coward not to visit the United States in January 1945. He did not return to America again during the war. In the aftermath of the war, Coward wrote an [[alternate history|alternative reality]] play, ''[[Peace in Our Time (play)|Peace In Our Time]]'', depicting an England occupied by [[Nazi Germany]].<ref name=lahr93 />\n\n=== Post-war career ===\nCoward's new plays after the war were moderately successful but failed to match the popularity of his pre-war hits.<ref>Lahr, p. 136</ref> ''[[Relative Values (play)|Relative Values]]'' (1951) addresses the culture clash between an aristocratic English family and a Hollywood actress with matrimonial ambitions; ''[[South Sea Bubble (play)|South Sea Bubble]]'' (1951) is a political comedy set in a British colony; ''[[Quadrille (play)|Quadrille]]'' (1952) is a drama about Victorian love and elopement; and ''[[Nude with Violin]]'' (1956, starring [[John Gielgud]] in London and Coward in New York) is a satire on modern art and critical pretension.<ref>Lesley, pp. 314, 370 and 361</ref> A revue, ''[[Sigh No More (musical)|Sigh No More]]'' (1945), was a moderate success,<ref>Morley (1974), p. 308</ref> but two musicals, ''[[Pacific 1860]]'' (1946), a lavish [[South Seas (genre)|South Seas]] romance, and ''[[Ace of Clubs (musical)|Ace of Clubs]]'' (1949), set in a night club, were financial failures.<ref>Lesley, pp. 248 and 289</ref> Further blows in this period were the deaths of Coward's friends Charles Cochran and Gertrude Lawrence, in 1951 and 1952 respectively. Despite his disappointments, Coward maintained a high public profile; his performance as King Magnus in Shaw's ''[[The Apple Cart]]'' for the Coronation season of 1953, co-starring [[Margaret Leighton]], received much coverage in the press,<ref>\"Haymarket Theatre\", ''The Times'', 8 May 1953, p. 12; and Brown, Ivor. \"Royal and Ancient\", ''The Manchester Guardian'', 8 May 1953, p. 5</ref> and his cabaret act, honed during his wartime tours entertaining the troops, was a supreme success, first in London at the [[Caf\u00e9 de Paris (London)|Caf\u00e9 de Paris]], and later in [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]].<ref>Morley (1974), pp. 339\u201340</ref> The theatre critic Kenneth Tynan wrote:\n{{quote|To see him whole, public and private personalities conjoined, you must see him in cabaret&nbsp;... he padded down the celebrated stairs{{space}}... halted before the microphone on black-suede-clad feet, and, upraising both hands in a gesture of benediction, set about demonstrating how these things should be done. Baring his teeth as if unveiling some grotesque monument, and cooing like a [[baritone]] dove, he gave us \"I'll See You Again\" and the other bat's-wing melodies of his youth. Nothing he does on these occasions sounds strained or arid; his tanned, leathery face is still an enthusiast's.... If it is possible to romp fastidiously, that is what Coward does. He owes little to earlier wits, such as [[Oscar Wilde|Wilde]] or [[Henry Labouch\u00e8re|Labouchere]]. Their best things need to be delivered slowly, even lazily. Coward's emerge with the staccato, blind impulsiveness of a machine-gun.<ref name=tynan />}}\n\nIn 1955 Coward's cabaret act at Las Vegas, recorded live for the gramophone, and released as ''[[No\u00ebl Coward at Las Vegas]]'',<ref>Reissued in 2003 on CD by CBS \u2013 DRG 19037</ref> was so successful that [[CBS]] engaged him to write and direct a series of three 90-minute television specials for the 1955\u201356 season. The first of these, ''Together With Music'', paired Coward with [[Mary Martin]], featuring him in many of the numbers from his Las Vegas act.<ref>Kenrick, John. [http://www.musicals101.com/noelbio3.htm \"Noel Coward \u2013 Biography, Part III\"], Coward 101 at ''Musicals 101: The Cyber Encyclopedia of Musical Theatre, TV and Film'', accessed 16 February 2009</ref> It was followed by productions of ''Blithe Spirit'' in which he starred with [[Claudette Colbert]], [[Lauren Bacall]] and [[Mildred Natwick]] and ''This Happy Breed'' with [[Edna Best]] and [[Roger Moore]]. Despite excellent reviews, the audience viewing figures were moderate.<ref>Payn and Morley, pp. 287\u201388, 304 and 314</ref>\n\n[[File:Private Lives Theatre De Lys.jpg|left|thumb|\"Dad's Renaissance\": Coward's popularity surged in the 1960s; this poster features [[Al Hirschfeld|Al Hirschfeld's]] drawing of Coward rather than the stars of this 1968 revival.]]\nDuring the 1950s and 1960s Coward continued to write musicals and plays. ''[[After the Ball (musical)|After the Ball]]'', his 1953 adaptation of ''[[Lady Windermere's Fan]]'', was the last musical he premiered in the West End; his last two musicals were first produced on Broadway. ''[[Sail Away (musical)|Sail Away]]'' (1961), set on a luxury cruise liner, was Coward's most successful post-war musical, with productions in America, Britain and Australia.<ref>Lesley, pp. 410\u201314, and 428\u201329</ref> ''[[The Girl Who Came to Supper]]'', a musical adaptation of ''[[The Sleeping Prince (play)|The Sleeping Prince]]'' (1963), ran for only three months.<ref>Lesley, p. 430</ref> He directed the successful 1964 Broadway musical adaptation of ''Blithe Spirit'', called ''[[High Spirits (musical)|High Spirits]]''. Coward's late plays include a farce, ''[[Look After Lulu!]]'' (1959), and a tragi-comic study of old age, ''[[Waiting in the Wings (play)|Waiting in the Wings]]'' (1960), both of which were successful despite \"critical disdain\".<ref>[[John Simon (critic)|Simon, John]]. [http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/theater/reviews/1773/ \"Waiting in the Wings\",] ''The NY Magazine'', 3 January 2000, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> Coward argued that the primary purpose of a play was to entertain, and he made no attempt at modernism, which he felt was boring to the audience although fascinating to the critics. His comic novel, ''Pomp and Circumstance'' (1960), about life in a tropical British colony, met with more critical success.<ref>Payn and Morley, pp. 451 and 453</ref>{{#tag:ref|Coward's fictional [[South Sea Islands]] colony, \"Samolo\", was loosely based on Jamaica, where he had a home; he used it as the setting not only for his novel, but for two plays (''[[Point Valaine]]'' and ''[[South Sea Bubble (play)|South Sea Bubble]]'') and a musical (''[[Pacific 1860]]'').<ref>Coward, ''Plays, Six'', p. xi</ref>|group= n}}\n\nCoward's final stage success came with ''Suite in Three Keys'' (1966), a trilogy set in a hotel penthouse suite. He wrote it as his swan song as a stage actor: \"I would like to act once more before I fold my bedraggled wings.\"<ref>Coward, ''Plays, Five'', introduction, unnumbered page</ref> The trilogy gained glowing reviews and did good box office business in the UK.<ref>Morley (1974), p. 375</ref> In one of the three plays, ''[[A Song at Twilight]]'', Coward abandoned his customary reticence on the subject and played an explicitly homosexual character. The daring piece earned Coward new critical praise.<ref>\"Noel Coward's Skeleton Feast\", ''The Times'', 15 April 1966, p. 16</ref> He intended to star in the trilogy on Broadway but was too ill to travel. Only two of the ''Suite in Three Keys'' plays were performed in New York, with the title changed to ''No\u00ebl Coward in Two Keys'', starring [[Hume Cronyn]].<ref>Hoare, p. 502</ref>\n\nCoward won new popularity in several notable films later in his career, such as ''[[Around the World in 80 Days (1956 film)|Around the World in 80 Days]]'' (1956), ''[[Our Man in Havana (film)|Our Man in Havana]]'' (1959), ''[[Bunny Lake Is Missing]]'' (1965), ''[[Boom! (film)|Boom!]]'' (1968) and ''[[The Italian Job]]'' (1969).<ref>Hoare, pp. 380, 414, 491, 507 and 508</ref> Stage and film opportunities he turned down in the 1950s included an invitation to compose a musical version of ''[[Pygmalion (play)|Pygmalion]]'' (two years before ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' was written), and offers of the roles of the king in the original stage production of ''[[The King and I]]'', and Colonel Nicholson in the film ''[[The Bridge on the River Kwai]]''.<ref>Hoare, pp. 387, 386, and 473</ref> Invited to play the title role in the 1962 film ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]'', he replied, \"No, no, no, a thousand times, no.\"<ref>Day, p. 310</ref> In the same year, he turned down the role of Humbert Humbert in ''[[Lolita (1962 film)|Lolita]]'', saying, \"At my time of life the film story would be logical if the 12-year-old heroine was a sweet little old lady.\"<ref>Richards, p. 83</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1960s and early 1970s successful productions of his 1920s and 1930s plays, and new revues celebrating his music, including ''[[Oh, Coward!]]'' on Broadway and ''[[Cowardy Custard]]'' in London, revived Coward's popularity and critical reputation. He dubbed this comeback \"Dad's Renaissance\".<ref>Hoare p. 479 ''et seq.''</ref> It began with a hit 1963 revival of ''Private Lives'' in London and then New York.<ref>Morley (1974), pp. 370\u201372</ref> Invited to direct ''Hay Fever'' with [[Edith Evans]] at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]], he wrote in 1964, \"I am thrilled and flattered and frankly a little flabbergasted that the National Theatre should have had the curious perceptiveness to choose a very early play of mine and to give it a cast that could play the Albanian telephone directory.\"<ref>Morley (1974), p. 369</ref>\n\nOther examples of \"Dad's Renaissance\" included a 1968 [[Off-Broadway]] production of ''Private Lives'' at the [[Lucille Lortel Theatre|Theatre de Lys]] starring [[Elaine Stritch]], [[Lee Bowman]] and [[Betsy von Furstenberg]], and directed by [[Charles Nelson Reilly]]. Despite this impressive cast, Coward's popularity had risen so high that the theatre poster for the production used an [[Al Hirschfeld]] caricature of Coward (''pictured'') {{#tag:ref|The caricature was also used in connection with other Coward works, for example on his album of his ballet suite, \"London Morning\" (1959; reissued in 1978 on LP on DRG SL 5180 with the Hirschfeld drawing on the cover)|group= n}} instead of an image of the production or its stars. The illustration captures how Coward's image had changed by the 1960s: he was no longer seen as the smooth 1930s sophisticate, but as the doyen of the theatre. As ''[[New Statesman|The New Statesman]]'' wrote in 1964, \"Who would have thought the landmarks of the Sixties would include the emergence of No\u00ebl Coward as the grand old man of British drama? There he was one morning, flipping verbal tiddlywinks with reporters about \"Dad's Renaissance\"; the next he was{{space}}... beside [[E. M. Forster|Forster]], [[T. S. Eliot]] and the [[Order of Merit|OMs]], demonstrably the greatest living English playwright.\"<ref>Ronald Bryden in ''The New Statesman'', August 1964, ''quoted'' in Hoare, p. 479</ref> ''Time'' wrote that \"in the 60s... his best work, with its inspired inconsequentiality, seemed to exert not only a period charm but charm, period.\"<ref name=Time1969 />\n\n=== Death and honours ===\n[[File:No\u00ebl Coward Theatre 3.JPG|thumb|right|The [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]]]]\nBy the end of the 1960s, Coward suffered from [[arteriosclerosis]] and, during the run of ''Suite in Three Keys'', he struggled with bouts of memory loss.<ref>Hoare, p. 501</ref> This also affected his work in ''The Italian Job'', and he retired from acting immediately afterwards.<ref>Lesley, p. 454</ref> Coward was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1969 and was elected a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]].<ref>[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U153506/COWARD_Sir_Noel?index=1&results=QuicksearchResults&query=0 \"Coward, Sir No\u00ebl\"], ''Who Was Who'', A & C Black, 1920\u20132008; online edition, Oxford University Press, December 2007, accessed 12 March 2009.</ref> He received a [[Tony Award]] for lifetime achievement in 1970.<ref>[http://www.noelcoward.net/html/chronology.html \"Chronology\"], The No\u00ebl Coward Society], May 2001, accessed 27 August 2008</ref> In 1972, he was awarded an honorary [[Doctor of Letters]] degree by the [[University of Sussex]].<ref>[https://www.sussex.ac.uk/webteam/gateway/file.php?name=list-of-honorary-graduates.pdf&site=76 \"List of Honorary Graduates\"], University of Sussex, accessed 17 December 2014</ref>\n\nCoward died at his home, [[Firefly Estate]], in [[Jamaica]] on 26 March 1973 of heart failure<ref name=timesobit /> and was buried three days later on the brow of Firefly Hill, overlooking the north coast of the island.<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d ed.: 2. McFarland & Company (2016) {{ISBN|0786479922}}</ref> A memorial service was held in [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]] in London on 29 May 1973, for which the [[Poet Laureate]], [[John Betjeman]], wrote and delivered a poem in Coward's honour, {{#tag:ref|\"We are all here today to thank the Lord for the life of Noel Coward.<br />Noel with two dots over the 'e'<br />And the firm decided downward stroke of the 'l'.<br />We can all see him in our mind's eye<br />And in our mind's ear<br />We can hear the clipped decided voice\".<ref>Lesley, p. 481</ref>|group= n}} John Gielgud and Laurence Olivier read verse and [[Yehudi Menuhin]] played [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]. On 28 March 1984 a memorial stone was unveiled by the [[Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon|Queen Mother]] in [[Poets' Corner]], [[Westminster Abbey]]. Thanked by Coward's partner, [[Graham Payn]], for attending, the Queen Mother replied, \"I came because he was my friend.\"<ref>Day, p. 725</ref>\n\nThe [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] in [[St Martin's Lane]], originally opened in 1903 as the New Theatre and later called the Albery, was renamed in his honour after extensive refurbishment, re-opening on 1 June 2006.<ref>Davies, Hugh. \"Coward is the toast of theatreland again\", ''The Daily Telegraph'', 1 July 2006, p. 14</ref> A statue of Coward by [[Angela Conner]] was unveiled by the Queen Mother in the foyer of the Theatre Royal, Drury Lane in 1998.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/230250.stm \"Coward statue unveiled\"], BBC news, 8 December 1998, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> There are also sculptures of Coward displayed in New York and Jamaica,<ref>[http://www.noelcoward.net/html/centenary.html \"Centenary Year \u2013 1999\"], The No\u00ebl Coward Society, accessed 10 March 2009 and Koss, p. 163</ref> and a bust of him in the library in Teddington, near where he was born.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1396400 |desc=Teddington Library|accessdate=|ps=none}}, accessed 3 July 2014</ref> In 2008 an exhibition devoted to Coward was mounted at the National Theatre in London.<ref name=byrne>Byrne, Ciar. [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/whats-inspiring-the-nol-coward-renaissance-771897.html \"What's inspiring the No\u00ebl Coward renaissance?\"] ''The Independent'', 21 January 2008, accessed on 17 March 2009</ref> The exhibition was later hosted by the [[Museum of Performance & Design]] in San Francisco and the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] in [[Beverly Hills]], California.<ref>[http://archive.constantcontact.com/fs078/1102539682978/archive/1102852501059.html \"Coward on the Coast\"], The No\u00ebl Coward Society, 27 November 2009</ref>\n\n=== Personal life ===\n[[File:Coward as Slightly.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Coward as [[Lost Boys (Peter Pan)|Slightly]] in ''[[Peter Pan]]'' in 1913]]\nCoward was homosexual but, following the convention of his times, this was never publicly mentioned.<ref name=C&N /> The critic Kenneth Tynan's description in 1953 was close to an acknowledgment of Coward's sexuality: \"Forty years ago he was Slightly in ''Peter Pan'', and you might say that he has been wholly in ''Peter Pan'' ever since. No private considerations have been allowed to deflect the drive of his career; like Gielgud and [[Terence Rattigan|Rattigan]], like the late Ivor Novello, he is a congenital bachelor.\"<ref name=tynan /> Coward firmly believed his private business was not for public discussion, considering \"''any'' sexual activities when over-advertised\" to be tasteless.<ref>Payn, p. 248</ref> Even in the 1960s, Coward refused to acknowledge his sexual orientation publicly, wryly observing, \"There are still a few old ladies in [[Worthing]] who don't know.\"<ref>Hoare, p. 509</ref> Despite this reticence, he encouraged his secretary Cole Lesley to write a frank biography once Coward was safely dead.<ref>Lesley, p. xvii</ref>\n\nCoward's most important relationship, which began in the mid-1940s and lasted until his death, was with the South African stage and film actor Graham Payn.<ref>Payn, ''passim''</ref> Coward featured Payn in several of his London productions. Payn later co-edited with [[Sheridan Morley]] a collection of Coward's diaries, published in 1982. Coward's other relationships included the playwright Keith Winter, actors [[Louis Hayward]] and [[Alan Webb (actor)|Alan Webb]], his manager [[John C. Wilson|Jack Wilson]] and the composer [[Ned Rorem]], who published details of their relationship in his diaries.<ref>Hoare, pp. 162\u201363, 258, 261\u201362, 275, 273\u201374, and 469\u201370</ref> Coward had a 19-year friendship with [[Prince George, Duke of Kent]], but biographers differ on whether it was platonic.<ref>Hoare, p. 122</ref> Payn believed that it was, although Coward reportedly admitted to the historian Michael Thornton that there had been \"a little dalliance\".<ref>[http://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/304572/Upstairs-life-of-a-royal-rogue \"Upstairs life of a royal rogue\"], ''[[The Daily Express]]'', 26 February 2012</ref> Coward said, on the duke's death, \"I suddenly find that I loved him more than I knew.\"<ref>Lesley, p. 231</ref>\n\nCoward maintained close friendships with many women, including the actress and author Esm\u00e9 Wynne-Tyson, his first collaborator and constant correspondent; [[Gladys Calthrop]], who designed sets and costumes for many of his works; his secretary and close confidante Lorn Loraine; the actresses Gertrude Lawrence, [[Joyce Carey]] and Judy Campbell; and \"his loyal and lifelong ''amiti\u00e9 amoureuse''\", [[Marlene Dietrich]].<ref>Lesley, p. 176</ref>\n\nIn his profession, Coward was widely admired and loved for his generosity and kindness to those who fell on hard times. Stories are told of the unobtrusive way in which he relieved the needs or paid the debts of old theatrical acquaintances who had no claim on him.<ref name=timesobit /> From 1934 until 1956, Coward was the president of the [[Actors Orphanage]], which was supported by the theatrical industry. In that capacity, he befriended the young [[Peter Collinson (film director)|Peter Collinson]], who was in the care of the orphanage. He became Collinson's godfather and helped him to get started in show business. When Collinson was a successful director, he invited Coward to play a role in ''The Italian Job''. Graham Payn also played a small role in the film.<ref>Payn and Morley, p. 668</ref>\n\n[[File:Sir Noel Coward Switzerland Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Coward in his home in Switzerland in 1972]]\nIn 1926, Coward acquired [[Goldenhurst Farm]], in [[Aldington, Kent]], making it his home for most of the next thirty years, except when the military used it during the Second World War.<ref>Clark, Ross. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/3337128/Mad-about-the-house.html \"Mad about the house\"], ''The Telegraph'', 24 November 2004, accessed 27 August 2016</ref> It is a [[Grade II* listed buildings in Kent|Grade II listed building]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1071221 |desc=Goldenhurst Manor|accessdate=|ps=none}}, accessed 24 August 2016</ref> In the 1950s, Coward left the UK for tax reasons, receiving harsh criticism in the press.<ref>Lesley, p. 355</ref> He first settled in [[Bermuda]] but later bought houses in Jamaica and Switzerland (in the village of [[Les Avants]], near [[Montreux]]), which remained his homes for the rest of his life.<ref>Lesley, p. 395</ref> His expatriate neighbours and friends included [[Joan Sutherland]], [[David Niven]], [[Richard Burton]] and [[Elizabeth Taylor]], and [[Julie Andrews]] and [[Blake Edwards]] in Switzerland<ref>Lesley, p. 437</ref> and [[Ian Fleming]] and his wife [[Ann Fleming|Ann]] in Jamaica. Coward was a witness at the Flemings' wedding, but his diaries record his exasperation with their constant bickering.<ref>Lesley, p. 310; and Payn and Morley, p. 463</ref>\n\nCoward's political views were conservative, but not unswervingly so: he despised the government of [[Neville Chamberlain]] for its policy of [[appeasement|appeasing]] Nazi Germany, and he differed sharply with Winston Churchill over the [[Edward VIII abdication crisis|abdication crisis]] of 1936. Whereas Churchill supported [[Edward VIII]]'s wish to marry \"his cutie\", [[Wallis, Duchess of Windsor|Wallis Simpson]], Coward thought the king irresponsible, telling Churchill, \"England doesn't wish for a Queen Cutie.\"<ref>Lesley, pp. 187 and 197</ref> Coward disliked propaganda in plays; \"The theatre is a wonderful place, a house of strange enchantment, a temple of illusion. What it most emphatically is not and never will be is a scruffy, ill-lit, fumed-oak drill hall serving as a temporary soap box for political propaganda.\"<ref name=m101>Kenrick, John. [http://www.musicals101.com/noelquot.htm \"Noel Coward 101: Cowardy Quotations\"], Musicals101.com, The Cyber Encyclopedia of Musical Theatre, TV and Film, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> Nevertheless, his own views sometimes surfaced in his plays: both ''Cavalcade'' and ''This Happy Breed'' are, in the words of the playwright [[David Edgar (playwright)|David Edgar]], \"overtly Conservative political plays written in the [[Bertolt Brecht|Brechtian]] epic manner.\"<ref>Kaplan, p. 4</ref> In religion, Coward was agnostic. He wrote of his views, \"Do I believe in God? I can't say No and I can't say Yes, To me it's anybody's guess.\"<ref>Coward (''Not Yet the Dodo''), p. 54.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Coward also said, \"I keep an open mind, but I will be somewhat surprised if St Peter taps me on the shoulder and says: 'This way, No\u00ebl Coward, come up and try your hand on the harp.' I am no harpist.\"<ref>Richards, pp. 64\u201365</ref>|group= n}}\n\nCoward spelled his first name with the [[Diaeresis (diacritic)|di\u00e6resis]] (\"''I'' didn't put the dots over the 'e' in No\u00ebl. The language did. Otherwise it's not No\u00ebl but Nool!\").<ref>Richards, p. 58</ref> The press and many book publishers failed to follow suit, and his name was printed as 'Noel' in ''The Times'', ''The Observer'' and other contemporary newspapers and books.{{#tag:ref|Even Cole Lesley's 1976 biography refers to Coward as \"Noel\": \"...I have also forgone the use of his beloved diaeresis over the 'e' in his name, having no wish to dizzy the eye of the reader.\"<ref name=lxx>Lesley, p. xx</ref>|group= n}} The papers of No\u00ebl Coward are held in the [[University of Birmingham]].{{#tag:ref|The papers were transferred from the flat of Mrs J. D. Hirst, No\u00ebl Coward's personal secretary, in January 2001.<ref>[http://calmview.bham.ac.uk/record.aspx?src=Catalog&id=XCOW \"No\u00ebl Coward Collection\"], [[University of Birmingham]], Cadbury Research Library, Special Collections, accessed 22 September 2016</ref>|group= n}}\n\n== Public image ==\n[[File:Coward with-cigarette-holder.jpg|thumb|right|The Coward image: with [[cigarette holder]] in 1930]]\n\"Why\", asked Coward, \"am I always expected to wear a dressing-gown, smoke cigarettes in a [[Cigarette holder|long holder]] and say 'Darling, how wonderful'?\"<ref>Richards, p. 59</ref> The answer lay in Coward's assiduous cultivation of a carefully crafted image. As a suburban boy who had been taken up by the upper classes he rapidly acquired the taste for high life: \"I am determined to travel through life first class.\"<ref>Richards, p. 28</ref> He first wore a dressing gown onstage in ''The Vortex'' and used the fashion in several of his other famous plays, including ''Private Lives'' and ''Present Laughter''.<ref>Sacheli, Robert. [http://www.dandyism.net/?p=258#more-258 \"Joyeux Noel\"], Dandyism.net, 16 December 2006, accessed 17 March 2009</ref><ref>''Private Lives'', Act II, ''passim''</ref> [[George Walden]] identifies him as a modern [[dandy]].<ref>Barbey D'Aurevilly, p. 45</ref> In connection with the National Theatre's 2008 exhibition, ''[[The Independent]]'' commented, \"His famous silk, polka-dot dressing gown and elegant cigarette holder both seem to belong to another era. But 2008 is proving to be the year that Britain falls in love with No\u00ebl Coward all over again.\"<ref name=byrne />\n\nAs soon as he achieved success he began polishing the Coward image: an early press photograph showed him sitting up in bed holding a cigarette holder: \"I looked like an advanced Chinese decadent in the last phases of dope.\"<ref>Castle, p. 66</ref> Soon after that, Coward wrote, \"I took to wearing coloured turtle-necked jerseys, actually more for comfort than for effect, and soon I was informed by my evening paper that I had started a fashion. I believe that to a certain extent this was true; at any rate, during the ensuing months I noticed more and more of our seedier West-End chorus boys parading about London in them.\"<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), p. 183</ref> He soon became more cautious about overdoing the flamboyance, advising [[Cecil Beaton]] to tone down his outfits: \"It is important not to let the public have a loophole to lampoon you.\"<ref>Hoare, p. 201</ref> However, Coward was happy to generate publicity from his lifestyle.<ref name=Kenrick2 /> In 1969 he told ''Time'' magazine, \"I acted up like crazy. I did everything that was expected of me. Part of the job.\" ''Time'' concluded, \"Coward's greatest single gift has not been writing or composing, not acting or directing, but projecting a sense of personal style, a combination of cheek and chic, pose and poise.\"<ref name=Time1969 />\n\nCoward's distinctive clipped diction arose from his childhood: his mother was deaf and Coward developed his staccato style of speaking to make it easier for her to hear what he was saying; it also helped him eradicate a slight lisp.<ref>Hoare, p. 16</ref> His nickname, \"The Master\", \"started as a joke and became true\", according to Coward. It was used of him from the 1920s onwards.<ref name=lxx /> Coward himself made light of it: when asked by a journalist why he was known as \"The Master\", he replied, \"Oh, you know \u2013 Jack of all trades, master of none.\"<ref>Richards, p. 65</ref> He could, however, joke about his own immodesty: \"My sense of my importance to the world is relatively small. On the other hand, my sense of my own importance to myself is tremendous.\"<ref>Richards, p. 67</ref> When a ''Time'' interviewer apologised, \"I hope you haven't been bored having to go through all these interviews for your [70th] birthday, having to answer the same old questions about yourself\", Coward rejoined, \"Not at all. I'm fascinated by the subject.\"<ref name=Time1969 />\n\n== Critical reputation and legacy ==\n{{Main|Cultural impact of No\u00ebl Coward}}\n\nThe playwright [[John Osborne]] said, \"Mr Coward is his own invention and contribution to this century. Anyone who cannot see that should keep well away from the theatre.\"<ref>[http://www.noelcoward.com/ \"Noel Coward\"], Introduction page to NoelCoward.com, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> Tynan wrote in 1964, \"Even the youngest of us will know, in fifty years' time, exactly what we mean by 'a very Noel Coward sort of person'.\"<ref name=tynan /> In praise of Coward's versatility, [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Lord Mountbatten]] said, in a tribute on Coward's seventieth birthday, \"There are probably greater painters than No\u00ebl, greater novelists than No\u00ebl, greater librettists, greater composers of music, greater singers, greater dancers, greater comedians, greater tragedians, greater stage producers, greater film directors, greater cabaret artists, greater TV stars. If there are, they are fourteen different people. Only one man combined all fourteen different labels \u2013 The Master.\"<ref>Day, p. 3</ref>\n\n[[File:Noel Coward (1963) by Erling Mandelmann - 2.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Coward in 1963]]\nTynan's was the first generation of critics to realise that Coward's plays might enjoy more than ephemeral success. In the 1930s, [[Cyril Connolly]] wrote that they were \"written in the most topical and perishable way imaginable, the cream in them turns sour overnight\".<ref>Lahr, p. 2</ref> What seemed daring in the 1920s and 1930s came to seem old-fashioned in the 1950s, and Coward never repeated the success of his pre-war plays.<ref name=tynan /> By the 1960s, critics began to note that underneath the witty dialogue and the [[Art Deco]] glamour of the inter-war years, Coward's best plays also dealt with recognisable people and familiar relationships, with an emotional depth and pathos that had been often overlooked.<ref>Kaplan, pp. 7\u201313</ref> By the time of his death, ''The Times'' was writing of him, \"None of the great figures of the English theatre has been more versatile than he\", and the paper ranked his plays in \"the classical tradition of [[William Congreve|Congreve]], [[Richard Sheridan|Sheridan]], Wilde and Shaw\".<ref name=timesobit>\"Obituary: Sir Noel Coward\", ''The Times'', 27 March 1973, p. 18</ref>\n\nA symposium published in 1999 to mark the centenary of Coward's birth listed some of his major productions scheduled for the year in Britain and North America, including ''Ace of Clubs, After the Ball, Blithe Spirit, Cavalcade, Easy Virtue, Hay Fever, Present Laughter, Private Lives, Sail Away, A Song at Twilight, The Young Idea'' and ''Waiting in the Wings'', with stars including Lauren Bacall, [[Rosemary Harris]], [[Ian McKellen]], [[Corin Redgrave]], [[Vanessa Redgrave]] and Elaine Stritch.<ref>Kaplan, pp. 217\u201321</ref> In another tribute, [[Tim Rice]] said of Coward's songs: \"The wit and wisdom of No\u00ebl Coward's lyrics will be as lively and contemporary in 100 years' time as they are today\",<ref name=m101 /> and many have been recorded by [[Damon Albarn]], [[Ian Bostridge]], [[The Divine Comedy (band)|The Divine Comedy]], [[Elton John]], [[Valerie Masterson]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[Michael Nyman]], [[Pet Shop Boys]], [[Vic Reeves]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], Joan Sutherland, [[Robbie Williams]] and others.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/twentieth-century-blues-the-songs-of-noel-coward/oclc/44734242&referer=brief_results \"Twentieth-century blues: the songs of Noel Coward\"], [http://www.worldcat.org/title/ian-bostridge-noel-coward-songbook/oclc/815766527&referer=brief_results \"Ian Bostridge: No\u00ebl Coward songbook\"]; and [http://www.worldcat.org/title/sutherland-sings-noel-coward-songs-from-bitter-sweet-after-the-ball-and-more-featuring-noel-coward/oclc/51236890&referer=brief_results \"Sutherland sings Noel Coward\"], WorldCat, accessed 5 December 2013</ref>\n\nCoward's music, writings, characteristic voice and style have been widely parodied and imitated, for instance in ''[[Monty Python]]'', ''[[Round the Horne]]'' and ''[[Privates on Parade]]''.<ref>\"Sir Noel (Pierce) Coward\", ''Cambridge Encyclopedia'', Vol. 69</ref><ref>Nichols, Peter: ''Privates on Parade'', Act 2, Scene 1 (\"No\u00ebl, No\u00ebl\")</ref> Coward has frequently been depicted as a character in plays,<ref>Hoare, Philip. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3642513/Manuscripts-and-the-Master.html \"Manuscripts and the Master\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 22 May 2005</ref><ref>Martin, Dominic. [http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/4361/making-dickie-happy ''Making Dickie Happy''], TheStage.co.uk., 27 September 2004, accessed 4 January 2009</ref> films, television and radio shows, for example, in the 1968 Julie Andrews film ''[[Star! (film)|Star!]]'' (in which Coward was portrayed by his godson, [[Daniel Massey (actor)|Daniel Massey]]),<ref>[http://www.timeout.com/film/reviews/75255/Star.html \"Star! (1968)\"] ''Time Out Film Guide'', accessed 16 February 2009</ref> the BBC [[sitcom]] ''[[Goodnight Sweetheart (TV series)|Goodnight Sweetheart]]''<ref>Grove, Valerie, \"Carrying on Kenneth's pain\", ''The Times'', 27 December 1997, p. 19 and \"Book Now\" ''[[The Independent]]'', 20 August 2008, p. 16</ref> and a BBC Radio 4 series written by [[Marcy Kahan]] in which Coward was dramatised as a detective in ''Design For Murder'' (2000), ''A Bullet at Balmain's'' (2003) and ''Death at the Desert Inn'' (2005), and as a spy in ''Blithe Spy'' (2002) and ''Our Man In Jamaica'' (2007), with [[Malcolm Sinclair (actor)|Malcolm Sinclair]] playing Coward in each.<ref>[http://www.noelcoward.net/html/audio.html \"Audio and Broadcasts\"], The No\u00ebl Coward Society, 2007, accessed 11 March 2009</ref> On stage, characters based on Coward have included Beverly Carlton in the 1939 Broadway play ''[[The Man Who Came to Dinner]]''.<ref>Isherwood, Charles. [http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117787685.html \"The Man Who Came to Dinner\",] ''Variety'', 28 July 2000, accessed 16 February 2009</ref> A play about the friendship between Coward and Dietrich, called ''[[Lunch with Marlene]]'', by Chris Burgess, ran at the [[New End Theatre]] in 2008. The second act presents a musical revue, including Coward songs such as \"Don't Let's Be Beastly to the Germans\".<ref name=TheStage>Vale, Paul. [http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/20351/lunch-with-marlene \"Lunch with Marlene\"], ''The Stage'', 9 April 2008, accessed 29 March 2010</ref>\n\nCoward was an early admirer of the plays of [[Harold Pinter]] and backed Pinter's film version of ''[[The Caretaker]]'' with a \u00a31,000 investment.<ref name=hoare458>Hoare, p. 458</ref> Some critics have detected Coward's influence in Pinter's plays.<ref>Hoare, p. 269</ref> Tynan compared Pinter's \"elliptical patter\" to Coward's \"stylised dialogue\".<ref name=hoare458 /> Pinter returned the compliment by directing the National Theatre's revival of ''Blithe Spirit'' in 1976.<ref>[http://www.haroldpinter.org/directing/directing_spirit.shtml \"Blithe Spirit by Noel Coward, The National Theatre, June 1976 (and tour)\"] at haroldpinter.org, 2003, accessed 7 March 2009</ref>\n\n== Plays ==\n:''For plays that were written more than two years before the original production, a date of composition is given and the second date given is the year when first produced (fp).''\n\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''The Last Chapter (Ida Collaborates)'' (1917), one-act comedy, co-written with Esm\u00e9 Wynne under their joint pen name, Esnomel\n* ''Woman and Whisky'' (1918), one-act play, co-written with Wynne\n* ''[[The Rat Trap]]'' (1918), play in four acts; fp 1926\n* ''[[I'll Leave It to You]]'' (1920), light comedy in three acts fp 1920<ref>Morley (2005), p.32</ref>\n* ''[[The Young Idea]]'' (1922), comedy of youth in three acts\n* ''[[Sirocco (play)|Sirocco]]'' (1921), play in three acts, revised 1927\n* ''[[The Better Half (play)|The Better Half]]'' (1922), comedy in one act\n* ''[[The Queen Was in the Parlour]]'' (1922), play in three acts, fp 1926\n* ''[[Weatherwise (play)|Weatherwise]]'' (1923), comedy in two scenes, fp 1932\n* ''[[Fallen Angels (play)|Fallen Angels]]'' (1925), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[The Vortex]]'' (1924), play in three acts\n* ''[[Hay Fever (play)|Hay Fever]]'' (1925), comedy\n* ''[[Easy Virtue (play)|Easy Virtue]]'' (1925), play in three acts\n* ''[[Semi-Monde]]'' originally ''Ritz Bar'' (1926), play in three acts, fp 1988\n* ''[[This Was a Man]]'' (1926), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[The Marquise]]'' (1927), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Home Chat (play)|Home Chat]]'' (1927), play in three acts\n* ''[[Private Lives]]'' (1930), intimate comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Post Mortem (Coward play)|Post Mortem]]'' (1932), play in eight scenes, fp 1992\n* ''[[Cavalcade (play)|Cavalcade]]'' (1931), play in three parts\n* ''[[Design for Living|Design For Living]]'' (1932), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Point Valaine]]'' (1934), play in three acts\n* ''[[Tonight at 8.30]]'' (1935/36), three programmes of the following one-act plays:\n** ''[[We Were Dancing]]'', ''[[The Astonished Heart]]'', ''[[Red Peppers]]'', ''[[Hands Across the Sea (play)|Hands Across the Sea]]'', ''[[Fumed Oak]]'', ''[[Shadow Play (play)|Shadow Play]]'', ''[[Ways and Means (play)|Ways and Means]]'', ''[[Still Life (play)|Still Life]]'', ''[[Family Album (play)|Family Album]]'', ''[[Star Chamber (play)|Star Chamber]]''\n* ''[[Present Laughter]]'' (1939), play in three acts, fp 1942\n* ''[[This Happy Breed]]'' (1939), play in three acts, fp 1942\n* ''[[Blithe Spirit (play)|Blithe Spirit]]'' (1941), play in three acts\n* ''[[Peace In Our Time (play)|Peace In Our Time]]'' (1947), play in two acts\n* ''Long Island Sound'' (1947), comedy adapted from his short story ''What Mad Pursuit?'', fp 1989 (Windsor gala performance)\n* ''[[South Sea Bubble (play)|South Sea Bubble]]'' (''Island Fling'' in US), (1951), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Relative Values (play)|Relative Values]]'' (1951), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Quadrille (play)|Quadrille]]'' (1952), romantic comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Nude with Violin]]'' (1956), comedy in three acts\n* ''Volcano'' (1957), play in two acts, Mill at Sonning, staged reading 1989; staged at the [[Vaudeville Theatre]], 2012.<ref>Walker, Tim. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/9490428/Volcano-at-Vaudeville-Theatre-Seven-magazine-review.html \"Volcano, at Vaudeville Theatre, Seven magazine review\"], ''The Telegraph'', 21 August 2012</ref>\n* ''[[Look After Lulu!]]'' (1959), three-act farce adapted from [[Georges Feydeau]]\n* ''[[Waiting in the Wings (play)|Waiting in the Wings]]'' (1960), play in three acts\n* ''Suite in Three Keys: [[A Song at Twilight]]; Shadows of the Evening; [[Come Into the Garden, Maud (play)|Come Into the Garden, Maud]]'' (1966), a trilogy\n* ''Star Quality'' (1967), Coward's last play, comedy in three acts, fp Bath, 1985\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Revues, musicals, operetta and songs ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[London Calling!]]'' (1922, 1923), revue in collaboration with Ronald Jeans\n* ''[[On with the Dance (musical)|On with the Dance]]'' (1924, 1925), revue\n* ''[[This Year of Grace]]'' (1927, 1928), revue, originally ''[[Charles B. Cochran]]'s 1928 Revue''\n* ''[[Bitter Sweet]]'' (1928, 1929), operetta\n* ''[[Words and Music (musical)|Words and Music]]'' (1932), revue\n* ''[[Conversation Piece (musical)|Conversation Piece]]'' (1933), comedy with music\n* ''[[Operette (musical)|Operette]]'' (1937), musical play\n* ''[[Set to Music]]'' (1939), revue (a Broadway rewrite of ''Words and Music'')\n* ''[[Sigh No More (musical)|Sigh No More]]'' (1945), revue\n* ''[[Pacific 1860]]'' (1946), musical romance\n* ''[[Ace of Clubs (musical)|Ace of Clubs]]'' (1949), musical play\n* ''[[After the Ball (musical)|After the Ball]]'' (1953), musical based on ''[[Lady Windermere's Fan]]''\n* ''[[Sail Away (musical)|Sail Away]]'' (1959\u201361), musical comedy\n* ''[[The Girl Who Came to Supper]]'' (1963), musical comedy based on ''[[The Sleeping Prince (play)|The Sleeping Prince]]''\n* ''[[Oh, Coward!]]'' (1972) revue\n* ''[[Cowardy Custard]]'' (1972) revue\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Songs ===\nCoward wrote more than three hundred songs. The No\u00ebl Coward Society's website, drawing on performing statistics from the publishers and the [[PRS for Music|Performing Rights Society]], names \"[[Mad About the Boy]]\" (from ''Words and Music'') as Coward's most popular song, followed, in order, by:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* \"[[I'll See You Again]]\" (''Bitter Sweet'')\n* \"[[Mad Dogs and Englishmen (song)|Mad Dogs and Englishmen]]\" (''Words and Music'')\n* \"[[If Love Were All]]\" (''Bitter Sweet'')\n* \"Someday I'll Find You\" (''Private Lives'')\n* \"I'll Follow My Secret Heart\" (''Conversation Piece'')\n* \"[[London Pride (song)|London Pride]]\" (1941)\n* \"A Room With a View\" (''This Year of Grace'')\n* \"Mrs Worthington\" (1934)\n* \"Poor Little Rich Girl\" (''On with the Dance'')\n* \"The Stately Homes of England\" (''Operette'')\n{{div col end}}\n\nIn the society's second tier of favourites are:\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* \"The Party's Over Now\" (''Words and Music'')\n* \"Dearest Love\" (''Operette'')\n* \"Dear Little Caf\u00e9\" (''Bitter Sweet'')\n* \"Parisian Pierrot\" (''London Calling!'')\n* \"Men About Town\" (''Tonight at 8.30'')\n* \"Twentieth Century Blues\" (''Cavalcade'')\n* \"Uncle Harry\" (''Pacific 1860'')\n* \"[[Don't Let's Be Beastly to the Germans]]\" (1943)\n* \"There Are Bad Times Just Around the Corner\" (''Globe Review'')\n* \"Dance, Little Lady\" (''This Year of Grace'')\n* \"Has Anybody Seen Our Ship?\" (''Tonight at 8.30'')\n* \"[[I Went to a Marvellous Party]]\" (''Set to Music'')\n* \"Nina\" (''Sigh No More'')\n* \"A Bar on the Piccola Marina\" (1954)\n* \"Why Must the Show Go On?\" (''Together With Music'')\n* \"Sail Away\" (''Ace of Clubs'' and ''Sail Away'')\n* \"Zigeuner\" (''Bitter Sweet'')<ref name=ncsongs />\n{{div col end}}\n\nCoward was no fan of the works of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]],{{#tag:ref|\"I went to ''[[Iolanthe]]''... beautifully done and the music lovely but dated. It's no use, I ''hate'' Gilbert and Sullivan\".<ref>Day, p. 125</ref>|group= n}} but as a songwriter was nevertheless strongly influenced by them. He recalled: \"I was born into a generation that still took light music seriously. The lyrics and melodies of Gilbert and Sullivan were hummed and strummed into my consciousness at an early age. My father sang them, my mother played them{{space}}... my aunts and uncles, who were legion, sang them singly and in unison at the slightest provocation.\"<ref>Programme note for ''[[Cowardy Custard]]'' (1972) quoting ''The No\u00ebl Coward Song Book''</ref> His colleague Terence Rattigan wrote that as a lyricist Coward was \"the best of his kind since [[W. S. Gilbert]].\"<ref>Day, p. 257</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Adaptations of Coward works===\n*''[[The Queen Was in the Parlour (film)|The Queen Was in the Parlour]]'', directed by [[Graham Cutts]] (UK, 1927, based on [[The Queen Was in the Parlour|the play of the same name]])\n*''[[Easy Virtue (1928 film)|Easy Virtue]]'', directed by [[Alfred Hitchcock]] (UK, 1928, based on [[Easy Virtue (play)|the play of the same name]])\n*''[[The Vortex (film)|The Vortex]]'', directed by [[Adrian Brunel]] (UK, 1928, based on [[The Vortex|the play of the same name]])\n*''[[Private Lives (film)|Private Lives]]'', directed by [[Sidney Franklin (director)|Sidney Franklin]], [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] (1931, based on [[Private Lives|the play of the same name]])\n* ''[[Tonight Is Ours]]'', directed by [[Stuart Armstrong Walker|Stuart Walker]], [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] (1933, based on the play ''[[The Queen Was in the Parlour]]'')<!--January 21, 1933-->\n*''[[Cavalcade (1933 film)|Cavalcade]]'', directed by [[Frank Lloyd]], [[20th Century Fox]] (1933, based on [[Cavalcade (play)|the play of the same name]])<!--April 15, 1933-->\n*''[[Bitter Sweet (1933 film)|Bitter Sweet]]'', directed by [[Herbert Wilcox]] (UK, 1933, based on [[Bitter Sweet|the operetta of the same name]])<!--31 August 1933-->\n*''[[Design for Living (film)|Design for Living]]'', directed by [[Ernst Lubitsch]], Paramount (1933, based on [[Design for Living|the play of the same name]])<!--December 29, 1933-->\n*''[[The Terrible Lovers]]'', directed by [[Marc All\u00e9gret]] (France, 1936, based on the play ''[[Private Lives]]'')\n*''[[Bitter Sweet (1940 film)|Bitter Sweet]]'', directed by [[W. S. Van Dyke]], Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (1940, based on [[Bitter Sweet|the operetta of the same name]])\n*''[[We Were Dancing (film)|We Were Dancing]]'', directed by [[Robert Z. Leonard]], Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (1942, based on the plays ''[[We Were Dancing]]'', ''[[Ways and Means (play)|Ways and Means]]'' and ''[[Private Lives]]'')\n*''[[This Happy Breed (film)|This Happy Breed]]'', directed by [[David Lean]], [[Universal Pictures|Universal]] (UK, 1944, based on [[This Happy Breed|the play of the same name]]) (Coward was also a producer)\n*''[[Blithe Spirit (1945 film)|Blithe Spirit]]'', directed by [[David Lean]] (UK, 1945, based on [[Blithe Spirit (play)|the play of the same name]]) (Coward was also a producer)\n*''[[Brief Encounter]]'', directed by [[David Lean]] (UK, 1945, based on the play ''[[Still Life (play)|Still Life]]'') (Coward was also a screenwriter and producer)\n*''[[The Astonished Heart (film)|The Astonished Heart]]'', directed by [[Terence Fisher]] (UK, 1950, based on [[The Astonished Heart|the play of the same name]]) (Coward was also a screenwriter)\n*''[[Meet Me Tonight]]'', directed by [[Anthony Pelissier]] (UK, 1952, based on the plays ''[[Ways and Means (play)|Ways and Means]]'', ''[[Red Peppers]]'', and ''[[Fumed Oak]]'')\n*''[[Pretty Polly (film)|Pretty Polly]]'', directed by [[Guy Green (filmmaker)|Guy Green]] (UK, 1967, based on the short story ''Pretty Polly Barlow'')\n*''[[Brief Encounter (1974 film)|Brief Encounter]]'', directed by [[Alan Bridges]] (UK, 1974, based on the play ''[[Still Life (play)|Still Life]]'')\n* ''[[Relative Values (film)|Relative Values]]'', directed by Eric Styles (UK, 2000, based on [[Relative Values (play)|the play of the same name]])\n*''[[Easy Virtue (2008 film)|Easy Virtue]]'', directed by [[Stephan Elliott]] (UK, 2008, based on [[Easy Virtue (play)|the play of the same name]])<ref name=galeimdb>[http://infotrac.galegroup.com/galenet/wes_ttda?cause=http%3A%2F%2Fgalenet.galegroup.com%2Fservlet%2FGLD%2Fform%3FlocID%3Dwes_ttda%26l%3D2&cont=&sev=temp&type=session&sserv=no ''Contemporary Authors Online''], Thomson Gale, 2004, accessed 30 December 2008: requires subscription; and [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0002021/filmoyear Noel Coward] at the IMDB database, accessed 12 March 2009</ref>\n\n===Actor===\n*''[[Hearts of the World]]'' (1918) (uncredited)\n*''[[The Scoundrel (1935 film)|The Scoundrel]]'' (1935) as Anthony Mallare\n*''[[Men Are Not Gods]]'' (1936) (uncredited)\n*''[[In Which We Serve]]'' (1942) as Captain E.V. Kinross (also a screenwriter, producer and co-director)\n*''[[Blithe Spirit (1945 film)|Blithe Spirit]]'' (1945) (uncredited narrator) (also producer)\n*''[[Brief Encounter]]'' (1945) (uncredited narrator) (also a screenwriter and co-producer)\n*''[[The Astonished Heart (film)|The Astonished Heart]]'' (1950) as Dr. Christian Faber\n*''Blithe Spirit'' (1956 TV film) as Charles Condomine\n*''[[Around the World in 80 Days (1956 film)|Around the World in 80 Days]]'' (1956) as Roland Hesketh-Baggott\n*''[[Our Man in Havana (film)|Our Man in Havana]]'' (1959) as Hawthorne\n*''[[Surprise Package (film)|Surprise Package]]'' (1960) as King Pavel II\n*''[[Paris When It Sizzles]]'' (1964) as Alexander Meyerheim\n*''Ninety Years On'' (1964 TV film) as Narrator / Host\n*''[[Bunny Lake Is Missing]]'' (1965) as Horatio Wilson\n*''Androcles and the Lion'' (1967 TV film) as Caesar\n*''[[Boom! (film)|Boom!]]'' (1968) as The Witch of Capri\n*''[[The Italian Job]]'' (1969) as Mr. Bridger\n\n== Notes and references ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|group=n|colwidth=24em}}\n\n'''References'''\n{{Reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book |last = Barbey D'Aurevilly |first = Jules |others = George Walden (trans. and ed. of new edition) |year = 2002 |origyear = 1845 |title = Who's a Dandy? \u2013 Dandyism and Beau Brummell |location = London |publisher = Gibson Square |isbn = 978-1-903933-18-3 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Castle |first = Charles |year = 1972 |title = No\u00ebl |location = London |publisher = W H Allen |isbn = 978-0-491-00534-0 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Coward |first = No\u00ebl |year = 1994 |others = Sheridan Morley (introduction) |title = Plays, Five |location = London |publisher = Methuen |isbn = 978-0-413-51740-1 |url-access = registration |url = https://archive.org/details/collectedplays00cowa }}\n* {{cite book | last=Coward | first=No\u00ebl | year=1994 | others=Sheridan Morley (introduction) | title=Plays, Six | location=London | publisher=Methuen | isbn=978-0-413-73410-5 | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/collectedplays00cowa }} \n* {{cite book |last = Coward |first = No\u00ebl |year = 2004 |title = Present Indicative \u2013 Autobiography to 1931 |origyear = 1932 |location = London |publisher = Methuen |isbn = 978-0-413-77413-2 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Coward |first = No\u00ebl |year = 1954 |title = Future Indefinite |location = London |publisher = Heinemann |oclc = 5002107 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Coward |first = No\u00ebl |year = 1967 |title = Not Yet the Dodo, and other verses |location = London |publisher = Heinemann |oclc = 488338862 }}\n* {{cite book |editor-last = Day |editor-first = Barry |year = 2007 |title = The Letters of No\u00ebl Coward |location = London |publisher = Methuen |isbn = 978-1-4081-0675-4 }}\n* {{cite book |editor-last = Gaye |editor-first = Freda |year = 1967 |title = Who's Who in the Theatre |edition = fourteenth |location = London |publisher = Sir Isaac Pitman and Sons |oclc = 5997224 }}\n* {{cite book|last= Herbert|first=Ian (ed) |year= 1977|title=Who's Who in the Theatre |edition=sixteenth|location=London and Detroit|publisher= Pitman Publishing and Gale Research |isbn=978-0-273-00163-8}}\n* {{cite book |last = Hoare |first = Philip |year = 1995 |title = No\u00ebl Coward, A Biography |location = London |publisher = Sinclair-Stevenson |isbn = 978-1-4081-0675-4 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last = Kaplan |editor1-first = Joel |editor2-first = Sheila |editor2-last = Stowel |year = 2000 |title = Look Back in Pleasure: No\u00ebl Coward Reconsidered |location = London |publisher = Methuen |isbn = 978-0-413-75500-1 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Koss |first = Richard |title = Jamaica |year = 2008 |location = London |publisher = Lonely Planet |isbn = 978-1-74104-693-9 |url = https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetjama00rich }}\n* {{cite book |last = Lahr |first = John |year = 1982 |title = Coward the Playwright |url = https://archive.org/details/cowardplaywright0000lahr |url-access = registration |location = London |publisher = Methuen |isbn = 978-0-413-48050-7 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Lesley |first = Cole |year = 1976 |title = The Life of No\u00ebl Coward |location = London |publisher = Cape |isbn = 978-0-224-01288-1 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Mander |first = Raymond |author2 = Mitchenson, Joe |author3 = Day, Barry Day |author4 = Morley, Sheridan |year = 2000 |edition = second |origyear = 1957 |title = Theatrical Companion to Coward |location = London |publisher = Oberon |isbn = 978-1-84002-054-0 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Morley |first = Sheridan |year = 1974 |origyear = 1969 |title = A Talent to Amuse |location = London |publisher = Penguin |isbn = 978-0-14-003863-7 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Morley |first = Sheridan |year = 2005| title = No\u00ebl Coward |location = London |publisher = Haus Publishing |isbn = 978-1-90-434188-8 }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last = Payn |editor1-first = Graham |editor2-first = Sheridan |editor2-last = Morley |year = 1982 |title = The No\u00ebl Coward Diaries (1941\u20131969) |location = London |publisher = Methuen |isbn = 978-0-297-78142-4 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Payn |first = Graham |year = 1994 |title = My Life with No\u00ebl Coward |location = New York |publisher = Applause Books |isbn = 978-1-55783-190-3 }}\n* {{cite book |editor-last = Richards |editor-first = Dick |year = 1970 |title = The Wit of No\u00ebl Coward |location = London |publisher = Sphere Books |isbn = 978-0-7221-3676-8 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Tynan |first = Kenneth |year = 1964 |title = Tynan on Theatre |url = https://archive.org/details/tynanontheatre0000tyna |url-access = registration |location = Harmondsworth, UK |publisher = Penguin |oclc = 949598 }}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last = Braybrooke |first = Patrick |year = 1933 |title = The Amazing Mr Noel Coward |location =  |publisher = Denis Archer |oclc = 1374995 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Coward |first = No\u00ebl |year = 1985 |title = The Complete Stories |location = London |publisher = Methuen |isbn = 978-0-413-59970-4 |url = https://archive.org/details/collectedshortst00cowa }}\n* {{cite book |last = Coward |first = No\u00ebl |year = 1986 |title = Past Conditional ''(third volume, unfinished, of autobiography)'' |location = London |publisher = Heinemann |isbn = 978-0-413-60660-0 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Coward |first = No\u00ebl |year = 1944 |title = Middle East Diary |location = London |publisher = Heinemann |oclc = 640033606 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Coward |first = No\u00ebl |editor = Barry Day |year = 1998 |title = Coward: The Complete Lyrics |location = London |publisher = Methuen |isbn = 978-0-413-73230-9 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Coward |first = No\u00ebl |editor = Barry Day |year = 2011 |title = The Complete Verse of No\u00ebl Coward |location = London |publisher = Methuen |isbn = 978-1-4081-3174-9 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Fisher |first = Clive |year = 1992 |title = No\u00ebl Coward |location = London |publisher = Weidenfeld |isbn = 978-0-297-81180-0 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Wynne-Tyson |first = Jon |year = 2004 |title = Finding the Words: A Publishing Life |location = Norwich |publisher = Michael Russell |isbn = 978-0-85955-287-5 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|wikt=no|b=no|q=No\u00ebl Coward|s=no|commons=Category:No\u00ebl Coward|n=no|v=no|species=no|d=Q298388|voy=no}}\n* {{Official Website}}\n* {{IMDb name|0002021}}\n\n'''Works'''\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Coward,+Noel | name=Noel Coward}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=No\u00ebl Coward |sopt=t}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=11459}}\n* [https://norman.hrc.utexas.edu/fasearch/html/lfcoward.html No\u00ebl Coward collection] in the [[Harry Ransom Center]] at the [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/audiointerviews/profilepages/cowardn1.shtml Audio (.ram files) of a 1969 interview] by [[Patrick Garland]] for the BBC\n\n'''Portals'''\n* [http://www.noelcoward.net/ The No\u00ebl Coward Society]\n* [http://www.musicals101.com/noel.htm No\u00ebl Coward 101] at the Cyber Encyclopedia of Musical Theatre, Television and Film\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090430012835/http://www.tonightat830.com/Coward-Timeline/ Coward timeline and photos of Coward]\n* [http://www.suttonelms.org.uk/NC.HTML Noel Coward plays on radio]\n* [http://archiveshub.ac.uk/data/gb71-thm/287 Esme Wynne and No\u00ebl Coward Collection], held by the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] Theatre and Performance Department.\n* [http://digilib.nypl.org/dynaweb/ead/nypl/brgcowar/@Generic__BookView Noel Coward collection of papers, 1919\u20131972] (28 items) are housed at the [[New York Public Library]].\n\n{{No\u00ebl Coward musicals}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for No\u00ebl Coward\n|list =\n{{Academy Honorary Award}}\n{{Special Tony Award}}\n}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Art|Biography|Film|LGBT|Music|United Kingdom}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coward, Noel}}\n[[Category:No\u00ebl Coward| ]]\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:Academy Honorary Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Actors awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Italia Conti Academy of Theatre Arts]]\n[[Category:Artists' Rifles soldiers]]\n[[Category:Cabaret singers]]\n[[Category:Composers awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:English composers]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:English lyricists]]\n[[Category:English male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English musical theatre composers]]\n[[Category:English male composers]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:LGBT composers]]\n[[Category:LGBT directors]]\n[[Category:LGBT dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT screenwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from England]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:MI5 personnel]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n[[Category:People from Teddington]]\n[[Category:Singers awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:LGBT memoirists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cardiac arrest]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English playwright, composer, director, actor and singer}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{bots|deny=Citation bot}}\n<!--Please review the discussions at and preceding https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:No%C3%ABl_Coward/Archive_2#RfC:_Should_an_Infobox_be_added_to_the_page? before considering adding an infobox -->\n[[File:Noel Coward Allan warren edit 1.jpg|thumb|Coward in 1972]]\n\n'''Sir No\u00ebl Peirce<!--YES, it is spelled PEIRCE--> Coward''' (16 December 1899{{snd}}26 March 1973) was an English playwright, composer, director, actor and singer, known for his wit, flamboyance, and what ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine called \"a sense of personal style, a combination of cheek and chic, pose and poise\".<ref name=Time1969>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,941819-2,00.html \"Noel Coward at 70\",] ''Time'', 26 December 1969, accessed 2 May 2011</ref>\n\nCoward attended a dance academy in London as a child, making his professional stage d\u00e9but at the age of eleven. As a teenager he was introduced into the high society in which most of his plays would be set. Coward achieved enduring success as a playwright, publishing more than 50 plays from his teens onwards. Many of his works, such as ''[[Hay Fever (play)|Hay Fever]]'', ''[[Private Lives]]'', ''[[Design for Living]]'', ''[[Present Laughter]]'' and ''[[Blithe Spirit (play)|Blithe Spirit]]'', have remained in the regular theatre repertoire. He composed hundreds of songs, in addition to well over a dozen musical theatre works (including the operetta ''[[Bitter Sweet]]'' and comic [[revue]]s), screenplays, poetry, several volumes of short stories, the novel ''Pomp and Circumstance'', and a three-volume autobiography. Coward's stage and film acting and directing career spanned six decades, during which he starred in many of his own works.\n\nAt the outbreak of the Second World War Coward volunteered for war work, running the British propaganda office in Paris. He also worked with the Secret Service, seeking to use his influence to persuade the American public and government to help Britain. Coward won an [[Academy Honorary Award]] in 1943 for his naval film drama ''[[In Which We Serve]]'' and was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1969. In the 1950s he achieved fresh success as a cabaret performer, performing his own songs, such as \"[[Mad Dogs and Englishmen (song)|Mad Dogs and Englishmen]]\", \"[[London Pride (song)|London Pride]]\" and \"[[I Went to a Marvellous Party]]\".\n\nCoward's plays and songs achieved new popularity in the 1960s and 1970s, and his work and style continue to influence popular culture. He did not publicly acknowledge his homosexuality, but it was discussed candidly after his death by biographers including [[Graham Payn]], his long-time partner, and in Coward's diaries and letters, published posthumously. The former Albery Theatre (originally the New Theatre) in London was renamed the [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] in his honour in 2006.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early years ===\nCoward was born in 1899 in [[Teddington]], [[Middlesex]], a south-western suburb of London. His parents were Arthur Sabin Coward (1856{{ndash}}1937), a piano salesman, and Violet Agnes Coward (1863{{ndash}}1954), daughter of [[s:A Naval Biographical Dictionary/Veitch, Henry Gordon|Henry Gordon Veitch]], a captain and surveyor in the [[Royal Navy]].<ref>Morley (1974), p. 2</ref> Violet's cousin, Rachel Veitch, was mother of Field-Marshal [[Douglas Haig, 1st Earl Haig|Douglas Haig]].<ref>Hoare, p. 2</ref> No\u00ebl Coward was the second of their three sons, the eldest of whom had died in 1898 at the age of six.<ref>Morley (1974), p. 3</ref> Coward's father lacked ambition and industry, and family finances were often poor.<ref>Morley (1974), pp. 4, 8 and 67</ref> Coward was bitten by the performing bug early and appeared in amateur concerts by the age of seven. He attended the [[Chapel Royal]] Choir School as a young child. He had little formal schooling but was a voracious reader.<ref name=Kenrick1>[[John Kenrick (theatre writer)|Kenrick, John]]. [http://www.musicals101.com/noelbio.htm \"Noel Coward \u2013 Biographical Sketch\"], Coward 101 at ''Musicals 101: The Cyber Encyclopedia of Musical Theatre, TV and Film'', 2000, accessed 9 March 2009</ref>\n\nEncouraged by his ambitious mother, who sent him to a dance academy in London,<ref>Hoare, p. 19</ref> Coward's first professional engagement was in January 1911 as Prince Mussel in the children's play ''The Goldfish''.<ref>\"The Little Theatre\", ''The Times'', 28 January 1911, p. 12</ref> In ''Present Indicative'', his first volume of memoirs, Coward wrote:\n{{quote|One day{{space}}... a little advertisement appeared in the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''.... It stated that a talented boy of attractive appearance was required by a Miss Lila Field to appear in her production of an all-children fairy play: ''The Goldfish.'' This seemed to dispose of all argument. I was a talented boy, God knows, and, when washed and smarmed down a bit, passably attractive. There appeared to be no earthly reason why Miss Lila Field shouldn't jump at me, and we both believed that she would be a fool indeed to miss such a magnificent opportunity.<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), pp. 21\u201322</ref>}}\n\n[[File:coward Hawtrey 1911.jpg|left|thumb|Coward ''(left)'' with [[Lydia Bilbrook]] ''(centre)'' and [[Charles Hawtrey (actor born 1858)|Charles Hawtrey]], 1911]]\nThe leading actor-manager [[Charles Hawtrey (actor born 1858)|Charles Hawtrey]], whom the young Coward idolised and from whom he learned a great deal about the theatre, cast him in the children's play ''[[Where the Rainbow Ends]]''. Coward played in the piece in 1911 and 1912 at the [[Garrick Theatre]] in London's [[West End theatre|West End]].<ref>Hoare, pp. 23\u201326</ref><ref name=times1912>\"Garrick Theatre\", ''The Times'', 12 December 1912, p. 8</ref> In 1912 Coward also appeared at the [[Savoy Theatre]] in ''An Autumn Idyll'' (as a dancer in the ballet) and at the [[London Coliseum]] in ''A Little Fowl Play'', by Harold Owen, in which Hawtrey starred.<ref>\"The Savoy Theatre\", ''The Times'', 26 June 1912, p. 10; \"The Coliseum\", 29 October 1912, p. 8; and \"Varieties etc\", 18 November 1912, p. 1</ref> [[Italia Conti Academy|Italia Conti]] engaged Coward to appear at the [[Liverpool Playhouse|Liverpool Repertory Theatre]] in 1913, and in the same year he was cast as the [[Lost Boys (Peter Pan)|Lost Boy]] Slightly in ''[[Peter and Wendy|Peter Pan]]''.<ref>\"The Cult of Peter Pan\", ''The Times'', 24 December 1913, p. 8</ref> He reappeared in ''Peter Pan'' the following year, and in 1915 he was again in ''Where the Rainbow Ends''.<ref>\"Fairies at the Garrick\", ''The Times'', 28 December 1915, p. 10</ref> He worked with other child actors in this period, including [[Hermione Gingold]] (whose mother threatened to turn \"that naughty boy\" out);<ref>Castle, p. 12</ref> [[Fabia Drake]]; [[Esm\u00e9 Wynne-Tyson|Esm\u00e9 Wynne]], with whom he collaborated on his earliest plays; Alfred Willmore, later known as [[Miche\u00e1l Mac Liamm\u00f3ir]]; and [[Gertrude Lawrence]] who, Coward wrote in his memoirs, \"gave me an orange and told me a few mildly dirty stories, and I loved her from then onwards.\"<ref name=times1912 /><ref>Hoare, pp. 27, 30 and 51</ref><ref name=times1916>\"The Happy Family\", ''The Times'', 19 December 1916, p. 11</ref>\n\n[[File:Noel Coward in his teens.jpg|upright=.57|thumb|right|Coward in his early teens]]\nIn 1914, when Coward was fourteen, he became the prot\u00e9g\u00e9 and probably the lover of [[Philip Streatfeild]], a society painter.<ref>Hoare, pp. 33\u201334</ref> Streatfeild introduced him to Mrs Astley Cooper and her high society friends.{{#tag:ref|Evangeline Julia Marshall, an eccentric society hostess (1854\u20131944), married Clement Paston Astley Cooper, grandson of [[Astley Paston Cooper|Sir Astley Paston Cooper]], on 10 July 1877. She inherited Hambleton Hall from her brother Walter Marshall (d. 1899), and there she entertained rising talents in the artistic world, including Streatfeild, the conductor [[Malcolm Sargent]] and the writer [[C. K. Scott Moncrieff|Charles Scott Moncrieff]], as well as the young Coward.<ref>[[Simon Callow|Callow, Simon]]. [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/apr/19/theatre \"Englishman abroad\",] ''The Guardian'', 19 April 2006, accessed 8 February 2009; [http://thepeerage.com/p25203.htm#i252021 \"Evangeline Julia Marshall\"], The Peerage, accessed 8 February 2009; and [http://www.hambletonhall.com/?about+us/Victorian-Hotel-History \"History\"], Hambleton Hall website, accessed 8 February 2009</ref>|group= n}} Streatfeild died from [[tuberculosis]] in 1915, but Mrs Astley Cooper continued to encourage her late friend's prot\u00e9g\u00e9, who remained a frequent guest at her estate, [[Hambleton Hall]].<ref>Hoare, pp. 39\u201343</ref>\n\nCoward continued to perform during most of the First World War, appearing at the [[Prince of Wales Theatre]] in 1916 in ''The Happy Family''<ref name=times1916 /> and on tour with [[Amy Brandon Thomas]]'s company in ''[[Charley's Aunt]]''. In 1917, he appeared in ''The Saving Grace'', a comedy produced by Hawtrey. Coward recalled in his memoirs, \"My part was reasonably large and I was really quite good in it, owing to the kindness and care of Hawtrey's direction. He took endless trouble with me{{space}}... and taught me during those two short weeks many technical points of comedy acting which I use to this day.\"<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), p. 66</ref>\n\nIn 1918, Coward was conscripted into the [[Artists Rifles]] but was assessed as unfit for active service because of a tubercular tendency, and he was discharged on health grounds after nine months.<ref>Lesley, pp. 41\u201342</ref> That year he appeared in the [[D. W. Griffith]] film ''[[Hearts of the World]]'' in an uncredited role. He sold short stories to several magazines to help his family financially.<ref name=Kenrick1 /> He also began writing plays, collaborating on the first two (''Ida Collaborates'' (1917) and ''Women and Whisky'' (1918)) with his friend Esm\u00e9 Wynne.<ref>[http://www.noelcoward.net/html/plays.html \"Plays and Musicals\"], The Noel Coward Society, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> His first solo effort as a playwright was ''[[The Rat Trap]]'' (1918) which was eventually produced at the [[Everyman Cinema, Hampstead|Everyman Theatre]], [[Hampstead]], in October 1926.<ref>Thaxter, John. [http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/rattrap-rev.htm \"The Rat Trap\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061215220640/http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/rattrap-rev.htm |date=15 December 2006 }} , British Theatre Guide, 2006, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> During these years, he met Lorn McNaughtan,{{#tag:ref|Later known by her married name, Lorn Loraine.<ref>Hoare, p. 79</ref>|group= n}} who became his private secretary and served in that capacity for more than forty years, until her death.<ref name=Kenrick1 />\n\n=== Inter-war successes ===\nIn 1920, at the age of 20, Coward starred in his own play, the light comedy ''[[I'll Leave It to You]]''. After a three-week run in [[Manchester]] it opened in London at the New Theatre (renamed the [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] in 2006), his first full-length play in the West End.<ref name=Thaxter>Thaxter, John. [http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/illleave-rev.htm ''I'll Leave It To You''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610013510/http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/illleave-rev.htm |date=10 June 2011 }} , British Theatre Guide, 2009</ref> [[Neville Cardus]]'s praise in ''[[The Guardian|The Manchester Guardian]]'' was grudging.<ref>Cardus, Neville. \"Gaiety Theatre\", ''[[The Manchester Guardian]]'', 4 May 1920, p. 13</ref> Notices for the London production were mixed, but encouraging.<ref name=Kenrick1 /> ''[[The Observer]]'' commented, \"Mr Coward... has a sense of comedy, and if he can overcome a tendency to smartness, he will probably produce a good play one of these days.\"<ref>Ervine, St John. \"At the Play\", ''The Observer'', 25 July 1920, p. 9</ref> ''The Times'', on the other hand, was enthusiastic: \"It is a remarkable piece of work from so young a head \u2013 spontaneous, light, and always 'brainy'.\"<ref>\"I'll Leave It to You\", ''The Times'', 22 July 1920, p. 10</ref>\n\n[[File:Coward pestle.jpg|left|thumb|upright=.57|Coward in ''[[The Knight of the Burning Pestle]]'' in 1920]]\nThe play ran for a month (and was Coward's first play seen in America),<ref name=Thaxter /> after which Coward returned to acting in works by other writers, starring as Ralph in ''[[The Knight of the Burning Pestle]]'' in [[Birmingham Repertory Theatre|Birmingham]] and then London.<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), pp. 104\u201305 and 112</ref> He did not enjoy the role, finding [[Francis Beaumont]] and his sometime collaborator [[John Fletcher (playwright)|John Fletcher]] \"two of the dullest Elizabethan writers ever known&nbsp;... I had a very, very long part, but I was very, very bad at it\".<ref>Castle, p. 38</ref> Nevertheless, ''The Manchester Guardian'' thought that Coward got the best out of the role,<ref>\"The Knight of the Burning Pestle\", ''The Manchester Guardian'', 25 November 1920, p. 14</ref> and ''The Times'' called the play \"the jolliest thing in London\".<ref>\"A Jacobean Romp\", ''The Times'', 25 November 1920, p. 10</ref>\n\nCoward completed a one-act satire, ''The Better Half'', about a man's relationship with two women. It had a short run at The Little Theatre, London, in 1922. The critic [[St. John Greer Ervine|St John Ervine]] wrote of the piece, \"When Mr Coward has learned that tea-table chitter-chatter had better remain the prerogative of women he will write more interesting plays than he now seems likely to write.\"<ref>Ervine, St John. \"New Grand Guignol Series\", ''The Observer'', 4 June 1922, p. 9</ref> The play was thought to be lost until a typescript was found in 2007 in the archive of the [[Lord Chamberlain's Office]], the official censor of stage plays in the UK until 1968.<ref>Thorpe, Vanessa. [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/sep/16/theatrenews.books \"Coward's long-lost satire was almost too 'daring' about women\",] ''The Observer'', 16 September 2007, accessed 22 September 2016</ref>\n\nIn 1921, Coward made his first trip to America, hoping to interest producers there in his plays. Although he had little luck, he found the Broadway theatre stimulating.<ref name=Kenrick1 /> He absorbed its smartness and pace into his own work, which brought him his first real success as a playwright with ''The Young Idea''. The play opened in London in 1923, after a provincial tour, with Coward in one of the leading roles.<ref>Hoare, pp. 89\u201391</ref> The reviews were good: \"Mr No\u00ebl Coward calls his brilliant little farce a 'comedy of youth', and so it is. And youth pervaded the Savoy last night, applauding everything so boisterously that you felt, not without exhilaration, that you were in the midst of a 'rag'.\"<ref>\"New Play at the Savoy\", ''The Times'', 2 February 1923, p. 8</ref> One critic, who noted the influence of [[George Bernard Shaw|Bernard Shaw]] on Coward's writing, thought more highly of the play than of Coward's newly found fans: \"I was unfortunately wedged in the centre of a group of his more exuberant friends who greeted each of his sallies with 'That's a No\u00eblism!'\"<ref>\"The Young Idea\", ''The Observer'', 4 February 1923, p. 11</ref>{{#tag:ref|Coward himself acknowledged that Shaw's ''[[You Never Can Tell (play)|You Never Can Tell]]'' was the primary inspiration for ''The Young Idea''.<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), p. 114</ref>|group= n}} The play ran in London from 1 February to 24 March 1923, after which Coward turned to [[revue]], co-writing and performing in [[Andr\u00e9 Charlot]]'s ''[[London Calling!]]''<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), pp. 112 and 150</ref>\n\n[[File:Lilian Braithwaite & No\u00ebl Coward.jpg|right|thumb|Coward with [[Lilian Braithwaite]], his co-star in ''[[The Vortex]]'' and the mother of his close friend [[Joyce Carey]]]]\nIn 1924, Coward achieved his first great critical and financial success as a playwright with ''[[The Vortex]].'' The story is about a nymphomaniac socialite and her cocaine-addicted son (played by Coward). Some saw the drugs as a mask for homosexuality;<ref>Hoare, p. 129</ref> [[Kenneth Tynan]] later described it as \"a [[jeremiad]] against narcotics with dialogue that sounds today not so much stilted as high-heeled\".<ref name=tynan>Tynan, pp. 286\u201388</ref> ''The Vortex'' was considered shocking in its day for its depiction of sexual vanity and drug abuse among the upper classes. Its notoriety and fiery performances attracted large audiences, justifying a move from a small suburban theatre to a larger one in the West End.<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), pp. 182\u201385</ref> Coward, still having trouble finding producers, raised the money to produce the play himself. During the run of ''The Vortex'', Coward met [[John C. Wilson|Jack Wilson]], an American stockbroker (later a director and producer), who became his business manager and lover. Wilson used his position to steal from Coward, but the playwright was in love and accepted both the larceny and Wilson's heavy drinking.<ref name=Kenrick2>Kenrick, John. [http://www.musicals101.com/noelbio2.htm \"Noel Coward \u2013 Biographical Sketch \u2013 Part II\"], Coward 101 at ''Musicals 101: The Cyber Encyclopedia of Musical Theatre, TV and Film'', 2000, accessed 9 March 2009</ref>\n\nThe success of ''The Vortex'' in both London and America caused a great demand for new Coward plays. In 1925 he premiered ''[[Fallen Angels (play)|Fallen Angels]]'', a three-act comedy that amused and shocked audiences with the spectacle of two middle-aged women slowly getting drunk while awaiting the arrival of their mutual lover.<ref>\"Fallen Angels\", ''The Manchester Guardian'', 23 April 1925, p. 12</ref> ''[[Hay Fever (play)|Hay Fever]]'', the first of Coward's plays to gain an enduring place in the mainstream theatrical repertoire, also appeared in 1925. It is a comedy about four egocentric members of an artistic family who casually invite acquaintances to their country house for the weekend and bemuse and enrage each other's guests. Some writers have seen elements of Coward's old mentor, Mrs Astley Cooper, and her set in the characters of the family.<ref>Hoare, pp. 42\u201343</ref> By the 1970s the play was recognised as a classic, described in ''The Times'' as a \"dazzling achievement; like ''[[The Importance of Being Earnest]]'', it is pure comedy with no mission but to delight, and it depends purely on the interplay of characters, not on elaborate comic machinery.\"<ref name=timesobit /> By June 1925 Coward had four shows running in the West End: ''The Vortex'', ''Fallen Angels'', ''Hay Fever'' and ''[[On with the Dance (musical)|On with the Dance]]''.<ref>Morley (1974), p. 107</ref> Coward was turning out numerous plays and acting in his own works and others'. Soon, his frantic pace caught up with him, and he collapsed on stage in 1926 while starring in a stage adaptation of ''[[The Constant Nymph (novel)|The Constant Nymph]]'' and had to take an extended rest, recuperating in [[Hawaii]].<ref name=Kenrick2 />\n\nOther Coward works produced in the mid-to-late 1920s included the plays ''[[Easy Virtue (play)|Easy Virtue]]'' (1926), a drama about a divorc\u00e9e's clash with her snobbish in-laws; ''[[The Queen Was in the Parlour]]'', a [[Ruritanian romance]]; ''[[This Was a Man]]'' (1926), a comedy about adulterous aristocrats; ''[[The Marquise]]'' (1927), an eighteenth-century costume drama; ''[[Home Chat (play)|Home Chat]]'' (1927), a comedy about a married woman's fidelity; and the revues ''On with the Dance'' (1925) and ''[[This Year of Grace]]'' (1928). None of these shows has entered the regular repertoire, but the last introduced one of Coward's best-known songs, \"A Room with a View\".<ref name=ncsongs>[http://www.noelcowardmusic.com/ncmi/appendices/appendix3.html \"Appendix 3 (The Relative Popularity of Coward's Works)\"], No\u00ebl Coward Music Index, accessed 29 November 2015</ref> His biggest failure in this period was the play ''[[Sirocco (play)|Sirocco]]'' (1927), which concerns free love among the wealthy. It starred [[Ivor Novello]], of whom Coward said, \"the two most beautiful things in the world are Ivor's profile and my mind\".<ref>Richards, p. 56</ref> Theatregoers hated the play, showing violent disapproval at the curtain calls and spitting at Coward as he left the theatre.<ref name=Kenrick2 /> Coward later said of this flop, \"My first instinct was to leave England immediately, but this seemed too craven a move, and also too gratifying to my enemies, whose numbers had by then swollen in our minds to practically the entire population of the British Isles.\"<ref>Richards, p. 26</ref>\n\nBy 1929 Coward was one of the world's highest-earning writers, with an annual income of \u00a350,000, more than \u00a32,800,000 in terms of 2018 values.<ref>[http://www.measuringworth.com/ppoweruk/ \"Purchasing Power of British Pounds from 1270 to the present\"], Measuring Worth website, accessed 6 June 2019</ref> Coward thrived during the [[Great Depression]], writing a succession of popular hits.<ref name=lahr93>Lahr, p. 93</ref> They ranged from large-scale spectaculars to intimate comedies. Examples of the former were the [[operetta]] ''[[Bitter Sweet]]'' (1929), about a woman who elopes with her music teacher,<ref name=C&N>Norton, Richard C. [http://operetta-research-center.org/coward-novello/ \"Coward & Novello\"], Operetta Research Center, 1 September 2007, accessed 29 November 2015</ref> and the historical extravaganza ''[[Cavalcade (play)|Cavalcade]]'' (1931) at [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]], about thirty years in the lives of two families, which required a huge cast, gargantuan sets and a complex hydraulic stage. Its [[Cavalcade (1933 film)|1933 film adaptation]] won the [[Academy Award]] for best picture.<ref>[http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1386188010849 \"Best Picture \u2013 1932/33 (6th)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221152803/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1386188010849 |date=21 February 2014 }}  Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, accessed 4 December 2013</ref> Coward's intimate-scale hits of the period included ''[[Private Lives]]'' (1930) and ''[[Design for Living]]'' (1932). In ''Private Lives'', Coward starred alongside his most famous stage partner, Gertrude Lawrence, together with the young [[Laurence Olivier]]. It was a highlight of both Coward's and Lawrence's career, selling out in both London and New York. Coward disliked long runs, and after this he made a rule of starring in a play for no more than three months at any venue.<ref name=Kenrick2 /> ''Design for Living'', written for [[Alfred Lunt]] and [[Lynn Fontanne]], was so risqu\u00e9, with its theme of bisexuality and a ''m\u00e9nage \u00e0 trois'', that Coward premiered it in New York, knowing that it would not survive the censor in London.<ref>Hoare, p. 249</ref>\n\n[[File:Novello-lunt-fontanne-campbell.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ivor Novello]], ''top l''., [[Alfred Lunt]], ''top r''., [[Lynn Fontanne]], ''lower l''. and [[Judy Campbell]]{{snd}}stars of Coward premi\u00e8res of the 1920s{{ndash}}1940s]]\nIn 1933 Coward wrote, directed and co-starred with the French singer [[Yvonne Printemps]] in both London and New York productions of an operetta, ''[[Conversation Piece (musical)|Conversation Piece]]'' (1933).<ref name=Kenrick2 /> He next wrote, directed and co-starred with Lawrence in ''[[Tonight at 8.30]]'' (1936), a cycle of ten short plays, presented in various permutations across three evenings.{{#tag:ref|The cycle effectively comprised only nine plays: although Coward wrote ten works for the cycle, ''[[Star Chamber (play)|Star Chamber]]'' was dropped after a single performance.<ref>Hoare, pp. 268\u201370</ref>|group= n}} One of these plays, ''[[Still Life (play)|Still Life]]'', was expanded into the 1945 [[David Lean]] film ''[[Brief Encounter]]''.<ref>Morley (1974), pp. 226\u201328 and 230</ref> ''Tonight at 8.30'' was followed by a musical, ''[[Operette (musical)|Operette]]'' (1938), from which the most famous number is \"The Stately Homes of England\", and a revue entitled ''[[Set to Music]]'' (1938, a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] version of his 1932 London revue, ''Words and Music'').<ref>Morley (1974), pp. 237 and 239</ref> Coward's last pre-war plays were ''[[This Happy Breed]]'', a drama about a working-class family, and ''[[Present Laughter]]'', a comic self-caricature with an egomaniac actor as the central character. These were first performed in 1942, although they were both written in 1939.<ref>Lahr, pp. 32 and 93</ref>\n\nBetween 1929 and 1936 Coward recorded many of his best-known songs for [[The Gramophone Company|His Master's Voice]] (HMV), now reissued on CD, including the romantic \"[[I'll See You Again]]\" from ''Bitter Sweet'', the comic \"[[Mad Dogs and Englishmen (song)|Mad Dogs and Englishmen]]\" from ''Words and Music'', and \"Mrs Worthington\".<ref>Naxos CDs 8.120559 and 8.120623</ref>\n\n=== Second World War ===\nWith the outbreak of the Second World War Coward abandoned the theatre and sought official war work. After running the British propaganda office in Paris, where he concluded that \"if the policy of His Majesty's Government is to bore the Germans to death I don't think we have time\",<ref>Richards, p. 105</ref> he worked on behalf of British intelligence.<ref>Koch, Stephen. [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/13/books/review/Koch-t.html \"The Playboy was a Spy\"], ''The New York Times'', 13 April 2008, accessed 4 January 2009</ref> His task was to use his celebrity to influence American public and political opinion in favour of helping Britain.{{#tag:ref|[[Harold Nicolson]], speaking for the Ministry of Information, stated that Coward \"possesses contacts with certain sections of opinion which are very difficult to reach through ordinary sources\".<ref>Lesley, p. 215</ref>|group= n}} He was frustrated by British press criticism of his foreign travel while his countrymen suffered at home, but he was unable to reveal that he was acting on behalf of the Secret Service.<ref name=hastings>Hastings, Chris. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1568190/Winston-Churchill-vetoed-Coward-knighthood.html \"Winston Churchill vetoed Coward knighthood\"], Telegraph.co.uk, 3 November 2007, accessed 4 January 2009</ref> In 1942 [[George VI]] wished to award Coward a knighthood for his efforts, but was dissuaded by [[Winston Churchill]]. Mindful of the public view of Coward's flamboyant lifestyle, Churchill used, as his reason for withholding the honour, Coward's \u00a3200 fine for contravening currency regulations in 1941.<ref name=hastings />\n\nHad the Germans invaded Britain, Coward was scheduled to be arrested and killed, as he was in [[The Black Book]] along with other figures such as [[Virginia Woolf]], [[Paul Robeson]], [[Bertrand Russell]], [[C. P. Snow]] and [[H. G. Wells]]. When this came to light after the war, Coward wrote: \"If anyone had told me at that time I was high up on the [[Nazi]] blacklist, I should have laughed&nbsp;... I remember [[Rebecca West]], who was one of the many who shared the honour with me, sent me a telegram which read: 'My dear \u2013 the people we should have been seen dead with'.\"<ref>Coward (''Future Indefinite''), p. 121</ref>\n\n[[File:Noel Coward Entertains the Men of the Eastern Fleet, HMS Victorious, Trincomalee, Ceylon, 1 August 1944 A25390.jpg|thumb|left|Coward, with [[Norman Hackforth]] at the piano, performing for sailors aboard {{HMS|Victorious|R38|6}} in Ceylon, August 1944]]\nChurchill's view was that Coward would do more for the war effort by entertaining the troops and the home front than by intelligence work: \"Go and sing to them when the guns are firing \u2013 that's your job!\"<ref>Morley (1974), p. 246</ref> Coward, though disappointed, followed this advice. He toured, acted and sang indefatigably in Europe, Africa, Asia and America.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,857528-1,00.html \"Light Entertainment\",] ''Time'', 19 July 1954, accessed 4 January 2009</ref> He wrote and recorded war-themed popular songs, including \"[[London Pride (song)|London Pride]]\" and \"[[Don't Let's Be Beastly to the Germans]]\". His London home was wrecked by German bombs in 1941, and he took up temporary residence at the [[Savoy Hotel]].<ref>Hoare, p. 317</ref> During one air raid on the area around the Savoy he joined [[Carroll Gibbons]] and [[Judy Campbell]] in impromptu cabaret to distract the captive guests from their fears.<ref>Hoare, p. 318</ref> Another of Coward's wartime projects, as writer, star, composer and co-director (alongside David Lean), was the naval film drama ''[[In Which We Serve]]''. The film was popular on both sides of the Atlantic, and he was awarded an [[Academy Honorary Award|honorary certificate of merit]] at the [[15th Academy Awards|1943 Academy Awards]] ceremony.<ref>[http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1386189663593 \"In Which we Serve\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20131205161150/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1386189663593 |date=5 December 2013 }} , Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, accessed 5 December 2013</ref> Coward played a naval captain, basing the character on his friend [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Lord Louis Mountbatten]]. Lean went on to direct and adapt film versions of several Coward plays.<ref name=Kenrick2 />\n\nCoward's most enduring work from the war years was the hugely successful black comedy ''[[Blithe Spirit (play)|Blithe Spirit]]'' (1941), about a novelist who researches the [[occult]] and hires a medium. A s\u00e9ance brings back the ghost of his first wife, causing havoc for the novelist and his second wife.<ref name=Kenrick2 /> With 1,997 consecutive performances, it broke box-office records for the run of a West End comedy, and was also produced on Broadway, where its original run was 650 performances.{{#tag:ref|The record (1,466 performances) had been held by ''[[Charley's Aunt]]'' since the 1890s.<ref>Gaye, p. 1525</ref> ''Blithe Spirit's'' West End record was overtaken by ''[[Boeing Boeing (play)|Boeing Boeing]]'' in the 1960s.<ref>Herbert, p. 1280</ref> The play was adapted into a [[Blithe Spirit (1945 film)|1945 film]], directed by Lean. Coward toured during 1942 in ''Blithe Spirit'', alternating the piece with his comedy ''Present Laughter'' and his working-class drama ''This Happy Breed''.<ref>Hoare, p. 331</ref>\n\nIn his ''Middle East Diary'' Coward made several statements that offended many Americans. In particular, he commented that he was \"less impressed by some of the mournful little [[Brooklyn]] boys lying there in tears amid the alien corn with nothing worse than a bullet wound in the leg or a fractured arm\".<ref>Calder, Robert. [https://books.google.com/books?id=HcpChZmn9s4C&pg=PA103&lpg=PA103#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Beware the British serpent''], p. 103</ref><ref>Hoare, p. 341</ref> After protests from both ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Washington Post]]'', the Foreign Office urged Coward not to visit the United States in January 1945. He did not return to America again during the war. In the aftermath of the war, Coward wrote an [[alternate history|alternative reality]] play, ''[[Peace in Our Time (play)|Peace In Our Time]]'', depicting an England occupied by [[Nazi Germany]].<ref name=lahr93 />\n\n=== Post-war career ===\nCoward's new plays after the war were moderately successful but failed to match the popularity of his pre-war hits.<ref>Lahr, p. 136</ref> ''[[Relative Values (play)|Relative Values]]'' (1951) addresses the culture clash between an aristocratic English family and a Hollywood actress with matrimonial ambitions; ''[[South Sea Bubble (play)|South Sea Bubble]]'' (1951) is a political comedy set in a British colony; ''[[Quadrille (play)|Quadrille]]'' (1952) is a drama about Victorian love and elopement; and ''[[Nude with Violin]]'' (1956, starring [[John Gielgud]] in London and Coward in New York) is a satire on modern art and critical pretension.<ref>Lesley, pp. 314, 370 and 361</ref> A revue, ''[[Sigh No More (musical)|Sigh No More]]'' (1945), was a moderate success,<ref>Morley (1974), p. 308</ref> but two musicals, ''[[Pacific 1860]]'' (1946), a lavish [[South Seas (genre)|South Seas]] romance, and ''[[Ace of Clubs (musical)|Ace of Clubs]]'' (1949), set in a night club, were financial failures.<ref>Lesley, pp. 248 and 289</ref> Further blows in this period were the deaths of Coward's friends Charles Cochran and Gertrude Lawrence, in 1951 and 1952 respectively. Despite his disappointments, Coward maintained a high public profile; his performance as King Magnus in Shaw's ''[[The Apple Cart]]'' for the Coronation season of 1953, co-starring [[Margaret Leighton]], received much coverage in the press,<ref>\"Haymarket Theatre\", ''The Times'', 8 May 1953, p. 12; and Brown, Ivor. \"Royal and Ancient\", ''The Manchester Guardian'', 8 May 1953, p. 5</ref> and his cabaret act, honed during his wartime tours entertaining the troops, was a supreme success, first in London at the [[Caf\u00e9 de Paris (London)|Caf\u00e9 de Paris]], and later in [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]].<ref>Morley (1974), pp. 339\u201340</ref> The theatre critic Kenneth Tynan wrote:\n{{quote|To see him whole, public and private personalities conjoined, you must see him in cabaret&nbsp;... he padded down the celebrated stairs{{space}}... halted before the microphone on black-suede-clad feet, and, upraising both hands in a gesture of benediction, set about demonstrating how these things should be done. Baring his teeth as if unveiling some grotesque monument, and cooing like a [[baritone]] dove, he gave us \"I'll See You Again\" and the other bat's-wing melodies of his youth. Nothing he does on these occasions sounds strained or arid; his tanned, leathery face is still an enthusiast's.... If it is possible to romp fastidiously, that is what Coward does. He owes little to earlier wits, such as [[Oscar Wilde|Wilde]] or [[Henry Labouch\u00e8re|Labouchere]]. Their best things need to be delivered slowly, even lazily. Coward's emerge with the staccato, blind impulsiveness of a machine-gun.<ref name=tynan />}}\n\nIn 1955 Coward's cabaret act at Las Vegas, recorded live for the gramophone, and released as ''[[No\u00ebl Coward at Las Vegas]]'',<ref>Reissued in 2003 on CD by CBS \u2013 DRG 19037</ref> was so successful that [[CBS]] engaged him to write and direct a series of three 90-minute television specials for the 1955\u201356 season. The first of these, ''Together With Music'', paired Coward with [[Mary Martin]], featuring him in many of the numbers from his Las Vegas act.<ref>Kenrick, John. [http://www.musicals101.com/noelbio3.htm \"Noel Coward \u2013 Biography, Part III\"], Coward 101 at ''Musicals 101: The Cyber Encyclopedia of Musical Theatre, TV and Film'', accessed 16 February 2009</ref> It was followed by productions of ''Blithe Spirit'' in which he starred with [[Claudette Colbert]], [[Lauren Bacall]] and [[Mildred Natwick]] and ''This Happy Breed'' with [[Edna Best]] and [[Roger Moore]]. Despite excellent reviews, the audience viewing figures were moderate.<ref>Payn and Morley, pp. 287\u201388, 304 and 314</ref>\n\n[[File:Private Lives Theatre De Lys.jpg|left|thumb|\"Dad's Renaissance\": Coward's popularity surged in the 1960s; this poster features [[Al Hirschfeld|Al Hirschfeld's]] drawing of Coward rather than the stars of this 1968 revival.]]\nDuring the 1950s and 1960s Coward continued to write musicals and plays. ''[[After the Ball (musical)|After the Ball]]'', his 1953 adaptation of ''[[Lady Windermere's Fan]]'', was the last musical he premiered in the West End; his last two musicals were first produced on Broadway. ''[[Sail Away (musical)|Sail Away]]'' (1961), set on a luxury cruise liner, was Coward's most successful post-war musical, with productions in America, Britain and Australia.<ref>Lesley, pp. 410\u201314, and 428\u201329</ref> ''[[The Girl Who Came to Supper]]'', a musical adaptation of ''[[The Sleeping Prince (play)|The Sleeping Prince]]'' (1963), ran for only three months.<ref>Lesley, p. 430</ref> He directed the successful 1964 Broadway musical adaptation of ''Blithe Spirit'', called ''[[High Spirits (musical)|High Spirits]]''. Coward's late plays include a farce, ''[[Look After Lulu!]]'' (1959), and a tragi-comic study of old age, ''[[Waiting in the Wings (play)|Waiting in the Wings]]'' (1960), both of which were successful despite \"critical disdain\".<ref>[[John Simon (critic)|Simon, John]]. [http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/theater/reviews/1773/ \"Waiting in the Wings\",] ''The NY Magazine'', 3 January 2000, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> Coward argued that the primary purpose of a play was to entertain, and he made no attempt at modernism, which he felt was boring to the audience although fascinating to the critics. His comic novel, ''Pomp and Circumstance'' (1960), about life in a tropical British colony, met with more critical success.<ref>Payn and Morley, pp. 451 and 453</ref>{{#tag:ref|Coward's fictional [[South Sea Islands]] colony, \"Samolo\", was loosely based on Jamaica, where he had a home; he used it as the setting not only for his novel, but for two plays (''[[Point Valaine]]'' and ''[[South Sea Bubble (play)|South Sea Bubble]]'') and a musical (''[[Pacific 1860]]'').<ref>Coward, ''Plays, Six'', p. xi</ref>|group= n}}\n\nCoward's final stage success came with ''Suite in Three Keys'' (1966), a trilogy set in a hotel penthouse suite. He wrote it as his swan song as a stage actor: \"I would like to act once more before I fold my bedraggled wings.\"<ref>Coward, ''Plays, Five'', introduction, unnumbered page</ref> The trilogy gained glowing reviews and did good box office business in the UK.<ref>Morley (1974), p. 375</ref> In one of the three plays, ''[[A Song at Twilight]]'', Coward abandoned his customary reticence on the subject and played an explicitly homosexual character. The daring piece earned Coward new critical praise.<ref>\"Noel Coward's Skeleton Feast\", ''The Times'', 15 April 1966, p. 16</ref> He intended to star in the trilogy on Broadway but was too ill to travel. Only two of the ''Suite in Three Keys'' plays were performed in New York, with the title changed to ''No\u00ebl Coward in Two Keys'', starring [[Hume Cronyn]].<ref>Hoare, p. 502</ref>\n\nCoward won new popularity in several notable films later in his career, such as ''[[Around the World in 80 Days (1956 film)|Around the World in 80 Days]]'' (1956), ''[[Our Man in Havana (film)|Our Man in Havana]]'' (1959), ''[[Bunny Lake Is Missing]]'' (1965), ''[[Boom! (film)|Boom!]]'' (1968) and ''[[The Italian Job]]'' (1969).<ref>Hoare, pp. 380, 414, 491, 507 and 508</ref> Stage and film opportunities he turned down in the 1950s included an invitation to compose a musical version of ''[[Pygmalion (play)|Pygmalion]]'' (two years before ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' was written), and offers of the roles of the king in the original stage production of ''[[The King and I]]'', and Colonel Nicholson in the film ''[[The Bridge on the River Kwai]]''.<ref>Hoare, pp. 387, 386, and 473</ref> Invited to play the title role in the 1962 film ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]'', he replied, \"No, no, no, a thousand times, no.\"<ref>Day, p. 310</ref> In the same year, he turned down the role of Humbert Humbert in ''[[Lolita (1962 film)|Lolita]]'', saying, \"At my time of life the film story would be logical if the 12-year-old heroine was a sweet little old lady.\"<ref>Richards, p. 83</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1960s and early 1970s successful productions of his 1920s and 1930s plays, and new revues celebrating his music, including ''[[Oh, Coward!]]'' on Broadway and ''[[Cowardy Custard]]'' in London, revived Coward's popularity and critical reputation. He dubbed this comeback \"Dad's Renaissance\".<ref>Hoare p. 479 ''et seq.''</ref> It began with a hit 1963 revival of ''Private Lives'' in London and then New York.<ref>Morley (1974), pp. 370\u201372</ref> Invited to direct ''Hay Fever'' with [[Edith Evans]] at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]], he wrote in 1964, \"I am thrilled and flattered and frankly a little flabbergasted that the National Theatre should have had the curious perceptiveness to choose a very early play of mine and to give it a cast that could play the Albanian telephone directory.\"<ref>Morley (1974), p. 369</ref>\n\nOther examples of \"Dad's Renaissance\" included a 1968 [[Off-Broadway]] production of ''Private Lives'' at the [[Lucille Lortel Theatre|Theatre de Lys]] starring [[Elaine Stritch]], [[Lee Bowman]] and [[Betsy von Furstenberg]], and directed by [[Charles Nelson Reilly]]. Despite this impressive cast, Coward's popularity had risen so high that the theatre poster for the production used an [[Al Hirschfeld]] caricature of Coward (''pictured'') {{#tag:ref|The caricature was also used in connection with other Coward works, for example on his album of his ballet suite, \"London Morning\" (1959; reissued in 1978 on LP on DRG SL 5180 with the Hirschfeld drawing on the cover)|group= n}} instead of an image of the production or its stars. The illustration captures how Coward's image had changed by the 1960s: he was no longer seen as the smooth 1930s sophisticate, but as the doyen of the theatre. As ''[[New Statesman|The New Statesman]]'' wrote in 1964, \"Who would have thought the landmarks of the Sixties would include the emergence of No\u00ebl Coward as the grand old man of British drama? There he was one morning, flipping verbal tiddlywinks with reporters about \"Dad's Renaissance\"; the next he was{{space}}... beside [[E. M. Forster|Forster]], [[T. S. Eliot]] and the [[Order of Merit|OMs]], demonstrably the greatest living English playwright.\"<ref>Ronald Bryden in ''The New Statesman'', August 1964, ''quoted'' in Hoare, p. 479</ref> ''Time'' wrote that \"in the 60s... his best work, with its inspired inconsequentiality, seemed to exert not only a period charm but charm, period.\"<ref name=Time1969 />\n\n=== Death and honours ===\n[[File:No\u00ebl Coward Theatre 3.JPG|thumb|right|The [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]]]]\nBy the end of the 1960s, Coward suffered from [[arteriosclerosis]] and, during the run of ''Suite in Three Keys'', he struggled with bouts of memory loss.<ref>Hoare, p. 501</ref> This also affected his work in ''The Italian Job'', and he retired from acting immediately afterwards.<ref>Lesley, p. 454</ref> Coward was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1969 and was elected a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]].<ref>[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U153506/COWARD_Sir_Noel?index=1&results=QuicksearchResults&query=0 \"Coward, Sir No\u00ebl\"], ''Who Was Who'', A & C Black, 1920\u20132008; online edition, Oxford University Press, December 2007, accessed 12 March 2009.</ref> He received a [[Tony Award]] for lifetime achievement in 1970.<ref>[http://www.noelcoward.net/html/chronology.html \"Chronology\"], The No\u00ebl Coward Society], May 2001, accessed 27 August 2008</ref> In 1972, he was awarded an honorary [[Doctor of Letters]] degree by the [[University of Sussex]].<ref>[https://www.sussex.ac.uk/webteam/gateway/file.php?name=list-of-honorary-graduates.pdf&site=76 \"List of Honorary Graduates\"], University of Sussex, accessed 17 December 2014</ref>\n\nCoward died at his home, [[Firefly Estate]], in [[Jamaica]] on 26 March 1973 of heart failure<ref name=timesobit /> and was buried three days later on the brow of Firefly Hill, overlooking the north coast of the island.<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d ed.: 2. McFarland & Company (2016) {{ISBN|0786479922}}</ref> A memorial service was held in [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]] in London on 29 May 1973, for which the [[Poet Laureate]], [[John Betjeman]], wrote and delivered a poem in Coward's honour, {{#tag:ref|\"We are all here today to thank the Lord for the life of Noel Coward.<br />Noel with two dots over the 'e'<br />And the firm decided downward stroke of the 'l'.<br />We can all see him in our mind's eye<br />And in our mind's ear<br />We can hear the clipped decided voice\".<ref>Lesley, p. 481</ref>|group= n}} John Gielgud and Laurence Olivier read verse and [[Yehudi Menuhin]] played [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]. On 28 March 1984 a memorial stone was unveiled by the [[Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon|Queen Mother]] in [[Poets' Corner]], [[Westminster Abbey]]. Thanked by Coward's partner, [[Graham Payn]], for attending, the Queen Mother replied, \"I came because he was my friend.\"<ref>Day, p. 725</ref>\n\nThe [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] in [[St Martin's Lane]], originally opened in 1903 as the New Theatre and later called the Albery, was renamed in his honour after extensive refurbishment, re-opening on 1 June 2006.<ref>Davies, Hugh. \"Coward is the toast of theatreland again\", ''The Daily Telegraph'', 1 July 2006, p. 14</ref> A statue of Coward by [[Angela Conner]] was unveiled by the Queen Mother in the foyer of the Theatre Royal, Drury Lane in 1998.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/230250.stm \"Coward statue unveiled\"], BBC news, 8 December 1998, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> There are also sculptures of Coward displayed in New York and Jamaica,<ref>[http://www.noelcoward.net/html/centenary.html \"Centenary Year \u2013 1999\"], The No\u00ebl Coward Society, accessed 10 March 2009 and Koss, p. 163</ref> and a bust of him in the library in Teddington, near where he was born.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1396400 |desc=Teddington Library|accessdate=|ps=none}}, accessed 3 July 2014</ref> In 2008 an exhibition devoted to Coward was mounted at the National Theatre in London.<ref name=byrne>Byrne, Ciar. [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/whats-inspiring-the-nol-coward-renaissance-771897.html \"What's inspiring the No\u00ebl Coward renaissance?\"] ''The Independent'', 21 January 2008, accessed on 17 March 2009</ref> The exhibition was later hosted by the [[Museum of Performance & Design]] in San Francisco and the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] in [[Beverly Hills]], California.<ref>[http://archive.constantcontact.com/fs078/1102539682978/archive/1102852501059.html \"Coward on the Coast\"], The No\u00ebl Coward Society, 27 November 2009</ref>\n\n=== Personal life ===\n[[File:Coward as Slightly.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Coward as [[Lost Boys (Peter Pan)|Slightly]] in ''[[Peter Pan]]'' in 1913]]\nCoward was homosexual but, following the convention of his times, this was never publicly mentioned.<ref name=C&N /> The critic Kenneth Tynan's description in 1953 was close to an acknowledgment of Coward's sexuality: \"Forty years ago he was Slightly in ''Peter Pan'', and you might say that he has been wholly in ''Peter Pan'' ever since. No private considerations have been allowed to deflect the drive of his career; like Gielgud and [[Terence Rattigan|Rattigan]], like the late Ivor Novello, he is a congenital bachelor.\"<ref name=tynan /> Coward firmly believed his private business was not for public discussion, considering \"''any'' sexual activities when over-advertised\" to be tasteless.<ref>Payn, p. 248</ref> Even in the 1960s, Coward refused to acknowledge his sexual orientation publicly, wryly observing, \"There are still a few old ladies in [[Worthing]] who don't know.\"<ref>Hoare, p. 509</ref> Despite this reticence, he encouraged his secretary Cole Lesley to write a frank biography once Coward was safely dead.<ref>Lesley, p. xvii</ref>\n\nCoward's most important relationship, which began in the mid-1940s and lasted until his death, was with the South African stage and film actor Graham Payn.<ref>Payn, ''passim''</ref> Coward featured Payn in several of his London productions. Payn later co-edited with [[Sheridan Morley]] a collection of Coward's diaries, published in 1982. Coward's other relationships included the playwright Keith Winter, actors [[Louis Hayward]] and [[Alan Webb (actor)|Alan Webb]], his manager [[John C. Wilson|Jack Wilson]] and the composer [[Ned Rorem]], who published details of their relationship in his diaries.<ref>Hoare, pp. 162\u201363, 258, 261\u201362, 275, 273\u201374, and 469\u201370</ref> Coward had a 19-year friendship with [[Prince George, Duke of Kent]], but biographers differ on whether it was platonic.<ref>Hoare, p. 122</ref> Payn believed that it was, although Coward reportedly admitted to the historian Michael Thornton that there had been \"a little dalliance\".<ref>[http://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/304572/Upstairs-life-of-a-royal-rogue \"Upstairs life of a royal rogue\"], ''[[The Daily Express]]'', 26 February 2012</ref> Coward said, on the duke's death, \"I suddenly find that I loved him more than I knew.\"<ref>Lesley, p. 231</ref>\n\nCoward maintained close friendships with many women, including the actress and author Esm\u00e9 Wynne-Tyson, his first collaborator and constant correspondent; [[Gladys Calthrop]], who designed sets and costumes for many of his works; his secretary and close confidante Lorn Loraine; the actresses Gertrude Lawrence, [[Joyce Carey]] and Judy Campbell; and \"his loyal and lifelong ''amiti\u00e9 amoureuse''\", [[Marlene Dietrich]].<ref>Lesley, p. 176</ref>\n\nIn his profession, Coward was widely admired and loved for his generosity and kindness to those who fell on hard times. Stories are told of the unobtrusive way in which he relieved the needs or paid the debts of old theatrical acquaintances who had no claim on him.<ref name=timesobit /> From 1934 until 1956, Coward was the president of the [[Actors Orphanage]], which was supported by the theatrical industry. In that capacity, he befriended the young [[Peter Collinson (film director)|Peter Collinson]], who was in the care of the orphanage. He became Collinson's godfather and helped him to get started in show business. When Collinson was a successful director, he invited Coward to play a role in ''The Italian Job''. Graham Payn also played a small role in the film.<ref>Payn and Morley, p. 668</ref>\n\n[[File:Sir Noel Coward Switzerland Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Coward in his home in Switzerland in 1972]]\nIn 1926, Coward acquired [[Goldenhurst Farm]], in [[Aldington, Kent]], making it his home for most of the next thirty years, except when the military used it during the Second World War.<ref>Clark, Ross. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/3337128/Mad-about-the-house.html \"Mad about the house\"], ''The Telegraph'', 24 November 2004, accessed 27 August 2016</ref> It is a [[Grade II* listed buildings in Kent|Grade II listed building]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1071221 |desc=Goldenhurst Manor|accessdate=|ps=none}}, accessed 24 August 2016</ref> In the 1950s, Coward left the UK for tax reasons, receiving harsh criticism in the press.<ref>Lesley, p. 355</ref> He first settled in [[Bermuda]] but later bought houses in Jamaica and Switzerland (in the village of [[Les Avants]], near [[Montreux]]), which remained his homes for the rest of his life.<ref>Lesley, p. 395</ref> His expatriate neighbours and friends included [[Joan Sutherland]], [[David Niven]], [[Richard Burton]] and [[Elizabeth Taylor]], and [[Julie Andrews]] and [[Blake Edwards]] in Switzerland<ref>Lesley, p. 437</ref> and [[Ian Fleming]] and his wife [[Ann Fleming|Ann]] in Jamaica. Coward was a witness at the Flemings' wedding, but his diaries record his exasperation with their constant bickering.<ref>Lesley, p. 310; and Payn and Morley, p. 463</ref>\n\nCoward's political views were conservative, but not unswervingly so: he despised the government of [[Neville Chamberlain]] for its policy of [[appeasement|appeasing]] Nazi Germany, and he differed sharply with Winston Churchill over the [[Edward VIII abdication crisis|abdication crisis]] of 1936. Whereas Churchill supported [[Edward VIII]]'s wish to marry \"his cutie\", [[Wallis, Duchess of Windsor|Wallis Simpson]], Coward thought the king irresponsible, telling Churchill, \"England doesn't wish for a Queen Cutie.\"<ref>Lesley, pp. 187 and 197</ref> Coward disliked propaganda in plays; \"The theatre is a wonderful place, a house of strange enchantment, a temple of illusion. What it most emphatically is not and never will be is a scruffy, ill-lit, fumed-oak drill hall serving as a temporary soap box for political propaganda.\"<ref name=m101>Kenrick, John. [http://www.musicals101.com/noelquot.htm \"Noel Coward 101: Cowardy Quotations\"], Musicals101.com, The Cyber Encyclopedia of Musical Theatre, TV and Film, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> Nevertheless, his own views sometimes surfaced in his plays: both ''Cavalcade'' and ''This Happy Breed'' are, in the words of the playwright [[David Edgar (playwright)|David Edgar]], \"overtly Conservative political plays written in the [[Bertolt Brecht|Brechtian]] epic manner.\"<ref>Kaplan, p. 4</ref> In religion, Coward was agnostic. He wrote of his views, \"Do I believe in God? I can't say No and I can't say Yes, To me it's anybody's guess.\"<ref>Coward (''Not Yet the Dodo''), p. 54.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Coward also said, \"I keep an open mind, but I will be somewhat surprised if St Peter taps me on the shoulder and says: 'This way, No\u00ebl Coward, come up and try your hand on the harp.' I am no harpist.\"<ref>Richards, pp. 64\u201365</ref>|group= n}}\n\nCoward spelled his first name with the [[Diaeresis (diacritic)|di\u00e6resis]] (\"''I'' didn't put the dots over the 'e' in No\u00ebl. The language did. Otherwise it's not No\u00ebl but Nool!\").<ref>Richards, p. 58</ref> The press and many book publishers failed to follow suit, and his name was printed as 'Noel' in ''The Times'', ''The Observer'' and other contemporary newspapers and books.{{#tag:ref|Even Cole Lesley's 1976 biography refers to Coward as \"Noel\": \"...I have also forgone the use of his beloved diaeresis over the 'e' in his name, having no wish to dizzy the eye of the reader.\"<ref name=lxx>Lesley, p. xx</ref>|group= n}} The papers of No\u00ebl Coward are held in the [[University of Birmingham]].{{#tag:ref|The papers were transferred from the flat of Mrs J. D. Hirst, No\u00ebl Coward's personal secretary, in January 2001.<ref>[http://calmview.bham.ac.uk/record.aspx?src=Catalog&id=XCOW \"No\u00ebl Coward Collection\"], [[University of Birmingham]], Cadbury Research Library, Special Collections, accessed 22 September 2016</ref>|group= n}}\n\n== Public image ==\n[[File:Coward with-cigarette-holder.jpg|thumb|right|The Coward image: with [[cigarette holder]] in 1930]]\n\"Why\", asked Coward, \"am I always expected to wear a dressing-gown, smoke cigarettes in a [[Cigarette holder|long holder]] and say 'Darling, how wonderful'?\"<ref>Richards, p. 59</ref> The answer lay in Coward's assiduous cultivation of a carefully crafted image. As a suburban boy who had been taken up by the upper classes he rapidly acquired the taste for high life: \"I am determined to travel through life first class.\"<ref>Richards, p. 28</ref> He first wore a dressing gown onstage in ''The Vortex'' and used the fashion in several of his other famous plays, including ''Private Lives'' and ''Present Laughter''.<ref>Sacheli, Robert. [http://www.dandyism.net/?p=258#more-258 \"Joyeux Noel\"], Dandyism.net, 16 December 2006, accessed 17 March 2009</ref><ref>''Private Lives'', Act II, ''passim''</ref> [[George Walden]] identifies him as a modern [[dandy]].<ref>Barbey D'Aurevilly, p. 45</ref> In connection with the National Theatre's 2008 exhibition, ''[[The Independent]]'' commented, \"His famous silk, polka-dot dressing gown and elegant cigarette holder both seem to belong to another era. But 2008 is proving to be the year that Britain falls in love with No\u00ebl Coward all over again.\"<ref name=byrne />\n\nAs soon as he achieved success he began polishing the Coward image: an early press photograph showed him sitting up in bed holding a cigarette holder: \"I looked like an advanced Chinese decadent in the last phases of dope.\"<ref>Castle, p. 66</ref> Soon after that, Coward wrote, \"I took to wearing coloured turtle-necked jerseys, actually more for comfort than for effect, and soon I was informed by my evening paper that I had started a fashion. I believe that to a certain extent this was true; at any rate, during the ensuing months I noticed more and more of our seedier West-End chorus boys parading about London in them.\"<ref>Coward (''Present Indicative''), p. 183</ref> He soon became more cautious about overdoing the flamboyance, advising [[Cecil Beaton]] to tone down his outfits: \"It is important not to let the public have a loophole to lampoon you.\"<ref>Hoare, p. 201</ref> However, Coward was happy to generate publicity from his lifestyle.<ref name=Kenrick2 /> In 1969 he told ''Time'' magazine, \"I acted up like crazy. I did everything that was expected of me. Part of the job.\" ''Time'' concluded, \"Coward's greatest single gift has not been writing or composing, not acting or directing, but projecting a sense of personal style, a combination of cheek and chic, pose and poise.\"<ref name=Time1969 />\n\nCoward's distinctive clipped diction arose from his childhood: his mother was deaf and Coward developed his staccato style of speaking to make it easier for her to hear what he was saying; it also helped him eradicate a slight lisp.<ref>Hoare, p. 16</ref> His nickname, \"The Master\", \"started as a joke and became true\", according to Coward. It was used of him from the 1920s onwards.<ref name=lxx /> Coward himself made light of it: when asked by a journalist why he was known as \"The Master\", he replied, \"Oh, you know \u2013 Jack of all trades, master of none.\"<ref>Richards, p. 65</ref> He could, however, joke about his own immodesty: \"My sense of my importance to the world is relatively small. On the other hand, my sense of my own importance to myself is tremendous.\"<ref>Richards, p. 67</ref> When a ''Time'' interviewer apologised, \"I hope you haven't been bored having to go through all these interviews for your [70th] birthday, having to answer the same old questions about yourself\", Coward rejoined, \"Not at all. I'm fascinated by the subject.\"<ref name=Time1969 />\n\n== Critical reputation and legacy ==\n{{Main|Cultural impact of No\u00ebl Coward}}\n\nThe playwright [[John Osborne]] said, \"Mr Coward is his own invention and contribution to this century. Anyone who cannot see that should keep well away from the theatre.\"<ref>[http://www.noelcoward.com/ \"Noel Coward\"], Introduction page to NoelCoward.com, accessed 8 February 2009</ref> Tynan wrote in 1964, \"Even the youngest of us will know, in fifty years' time, exactly what we mean by 'a very Noel Coward sort of person'.\"<ref name=tynan /> In praise of Coward's versatility, [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Lord Mountbatten]] said, in a tribute on Coward's seventieth birthday, \"There are probably greater painters than No\u00ebl, greater novelists than No\u00ebl, greater librettists, greater composers of music, greater singers, greater dancers, greater comedians, greater tragedians, greater stage producers, greater film directors, greater cabaret artists, greater TV stars. If there are, they are fourteen different people. Only one man combined all fourteen different labels \u2013 The Master.\"<ref>Day, p. 3</ref>\n\n[[File:Noel Coward (1963) by Erling Mandelmann - 2.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Coward in 1963]]\nTynan's was the first generation of critics to realise that Coward's plays might enjoy more than ephemeral success. In the 1930s, [[Cyril Connolly]] wrote that they were \"written in the most topical and perishable way imaginable, the cream in them turns sour overnight\".<ref>Lahr, p. 2</ref> What seemed daring in the 1920s and 1930s came to seem old-fashioned in the 1950s, and Coward never repeated the success of his pre-war plays.<ref name=tynan /> By the 1960s, critics began to note that underneath the witty dialogue and the [[Art Deco]] glamour of the inter-war years, Coward's best plays also dealt with recognisable people and familiar relationships, with an emotional depth and pathos that had been often overlooked.<ref>Kaplan, pp. 7\u201313</ref> By the time of his death, ''The Times'' was writing of him, \"None of the great figures of the English theatre has been more versatile than he\", and the paper ranked his plays in \"the classical tradition of [[William Congreve|Congreve]], [[Richard Sheridan|Sheridan]], Wilde and Shaw\".<ref name=timesobit>\"Obituary: Sir Noel Coward\", ''The Times'', 27 March 1973, p. 18</ref>\n\nA symposium published in 1999 to mark the centenary of Coward's birth listed some of his major productions scheduled for the year in Britain and North America, including ''Ace of Clubs, After the Ball, Blithe Spirit, Cavalcade, Easy Virtue, Hay Fever, Present Laughter, Private Lives, Sail Away, A Song at Twilight, The Young Idea'' and ''Waiting in the Wings'', with stars including Lauren Bacall, [[Rosemary Harris]], [[Ian McKellen]], [[Corin Redgrave]], [[Vanessa Redgrave]] and Elaine Stritch.<ref>Kaplan, pp. 217\u201321</ref> In another tribute, [[Tim Rice]] said of Coward's songs: \"The wit and wisdom of No\u00ebl Coward's lyrics will be as lively and contemporary in 100 years' time as they are today\",<ref name=m101 /> and many have been recorded by [[Damon Albarn]], [[Ian Bostridge]], [[The Divine Comedy (band)|The Divine Comedy]], [[Elton John]], [[Valerie Masterson]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[Michael Nyman]], [[Pet Shop Boys]], [[Vic Reeves]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], Joan Sutherland, [[Robbie Williams]] and others.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/twentieth-century-blues-the-songs-of-noel-coward/oclc/44734242&referer=brief_results \"Twentieth-century blues: the songs of Noel Coward\"], [http://www.worldcat.org/title/ian-bostridge-noel-coward-songbook/oclc/815766527&referer=brief_results \"Ian Bostridge: No\u00ebl Coward songbook\"]; and [http://www.worldcat.org/title/sutherland-sings-noel-coward-songs-from-bitter-sweet-after-the-ball-and-more-featuring-noel-coward/oclc/51236890&referer=brief_results \"Sutherland sings Noel Coward\"], WorldCat, accessed 5 December 2013</ref>\n\nCoward's music, writings, characteristic voice and style have been widely parodied and imitated, for instance in ''[[Monty Python]]'', ''[[Round the Horne]]'' and ''[[Privates on Parade]]''.<ref>\"Sir Noel (Pierce) Coward\", ''Cambridge Encyclopedia'', Vol. 69</ref><ref>Nichols, Peter: ''Privates on Parade'', Act 2, Scene 1 (\"No\u00ebl, No\u00ebl\")</ref> Coward has frequently been depicted as a character in plays,<ref>Hoare, Philip. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3642513/Manuscripts-and-the-Master.html \"Manuscripts and the Master\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 22 May 2005</ref><ref>Martin, Dominic. [http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/4361/making-dickie-happy ''Making Dickie Happy''], TheStage.co.uk., 27 September 2004, accessed 4 January 2009</ref> films, television and radio shows, for example, in the 1968 Julie Andrews film ''[[Star! (film)|Star!]]'' (in which Coward was portrayed by his godson, [[Daniel Massey (actor)|Daniel Massey]]),<ref>[http://www.timeout.com/film/reviews/75255/Star.html \"Star! (1968)\"] ''Time Out Film Guide'', accessed 16 February 2009</ref> the BBC [[sitcom]] ''[[Goodnight Sweetheart (TV series)|Goodnight Sweetheart]]''<ref>Grove, Valerie, \"Carrying on Kenneth's pain\", ''The Times'', 27 December 1997, p. 19 and \"Book Now\" ''[[The Independent]]'', 20 August 2008, p. 16</ref> and a BBC Radio 4 series written by [[Marcy Kahan]] in which Coward was dramatised as a detective in ''Design For Murder'' (2000), ''A Bullet at Balmain's'' (2003) and ''Death at the Desert Inn'' (2005), and as a spy in ''Blithe Spy'' (2002) and ''Our Man In Jamaica'' (2007), with [[Malcolm Sinclair (actor)|Malcolm Sinclair]] playing Coward in each.<ref>[http://www.noelcoward.net/html/audio.html \"Audio and Broadcasts\"], The No\u00ebl Coward Society, 2007, accessed 11 March 2009</ref> On stage, characters based on Coward have included Beverly Carlton in the 1939 Broadway play ''[[The Man Who Came to Dinner]]''.<ref>Isherwood, Charles. [http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117787685.html \"The Man Who Came to Dinner\",] ''Variety'', 28 July 2000, accessed 16 February 2009</ref> A play about the friendship between Coward and Dietrich, called ''[[Lunch with Marlene]]'', by Chris Burgess, ran at the [[New End Theatre]] in 2008. The second act presents a musical revue, including Coward songs such as \"Don't Let's Be Beastly to the Germans\".<ref name=TheStage>Vale, Paul. [http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/20351/lunch-with-marlene \"Lunch with Marlene\"], ''The Stage'', 9 April 2008, accessed 29 March 2010</ref>\n\nCoward was an early admirer of the plays of [[Harold Pinter]] and backed Pinter's film version of ''[[The Caretaker]]'' with a \u00a31,000 investment.<ref name=hoare458>Hoare, p. 458</ref> Some critics have detected Coward's influence in Pinter's plays.<ref>Hoare, p. 269</ref> Tynan compared Pinter's \"elliptical patter\" to Coward's \"stylised dialogue\".<ref name=hoare458 /> Pinter returned the compliment by directing the National Theatre's revival of ''Blithe Spirit'' in 1976.<ref>[http://www.haroldpinter.org/directing/directing_spirit.shtml \"Blithe Spirit by Noel Coward, The National Theatre, June 1976 (and tour)\"] at haroldpinter.org, 2003, accessed 7 March 2009</ref>\n\n== Plays ==\n:''For plays that were written more than two years before the original production, a date of composition is given and the second date given is the year when first produced (fp).''\n\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''The Last Chapter (Ida Collaborates)'' (1917), one-act comedy, co-written with Esm\u00e9 Wynne under their joint pen name, Esnomel\n* ''Woman and Whisky'' (1918), one-act play, co-written with Wynne\n* ''[[The Rat Trap]]'' (1918), play in four acts; fp 1926\n* ''[[I'll Leave It to You]]'' (1920), light comedy in three acts fp 1920<ref>Morley (2005), p.32</ref>\n* ''[[The Young Idea]]'' (1922), comedy of youth in three acts\n* ''[[Sirocco (play)|Sirocco]]'' (1921), play in three acts, revised 1927\n* ''[[The Better Half (play)|The Better Half]]'' (1922), comedy in one act\n* ''[[The Queen Was in the Parlour]]'' (1922), play in three acts, fp 1926\n* ''[[Weatherwise (play)|Weatherwise]]'' (1923), comedy in two scenes, fp 1932\n* ''[[Fallen Angels (play)|Fallen Angels]]'' (1925), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[The Vortex]]'' (1924), play in three acts\n* ''[[Hay Fever (play)|Hay Fever]]'' (1925), comedy\n* ''[[Easy Virtue (play)|Easy Virtue]]'' (1925), play in three acts\n* ''[[Semi-Monde]]'' originally ''Ritz Bar'' (1926), play in three acts, fp 1988\n* ''[[This Was a Man]]'' (1926), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[The Marquise]]'' (1927), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Home Chat (play)|Home Chat]]'' (1927), play in three acts\n* ''[[Private Lives]]'' (1930), intimate comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Post Mortem (Coward play)|Post Mortem]]'' (1932), play in eight scenes, fp 1992\n* ''[[Cavalcade (play)|Cavalcade]]'' (1931), play in three parts\n* ''[[Design for Living|Design For Living]]'' (1932), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Point Valaine]]'' (1934), play in three acts\n* ''[[Tonight at 8.30]]'' (1935/36), three programmes of the following one-act plays:\n** ''[[We Were Dancing]]'', ''[[The Astonished Heart]]'', ''[[Red Peppers]]'', ''[[Hands Across the Sea (play)|Hands Across the Sea]]'', ''[[Fumed Oak]]'', ''[[Shadow Play (play)|Shadow Play]]'', ''[[Ways and Means (play)|Ways and Means]]'', ''[[Still Life (play)|Still Life]]'', ''[[Family Album (play)|Family Album]]'', ''[[Star Chamber (play)|Star Chamber]]''\n* ''[[Present Laughter]]'' (1939), play in three acts, fp 1942\n* ''[[This Happy Breed]]'' (1939), play in three acts, fp 1942\n* ''[[Blithe Spirit (play)|Blithe Spirit]]'' (1941), play in three acts\n* ''[[Peace In Our Time (play)|Peace In Our Time]]'' (1947), play in two acts\n* ''Long Island Sound'' (1947), comedy adapted from his short story ''What Mad Pursuit?'', fp 1989 (Windsor gala performance)\n* ''[[South Sea Bubble (play)|South Sea Bubble]]'' (''Island Fling'' in US), (1951), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Relative Values (play)|Relative Values]]'' (1951), comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Quadrille (play)|Quadrille]]'' (1952), romantic comedy in three acts\n* ''[[Nude with Violin]]'' (1956), comedy in three acts\n* ''Volcano'' (1957), play in two acts, Mill at Sonning, staged reading 1989; staged at the [[Vaudeville Theatre]], 2012.<ref>Walker, Tim. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/9490428/Volcano-at-Vaudeville-Theatre-Seven-magazine-review.html \"Volcano, at Vaudeville Theatre, Seven magazine review\"], ''The Telegraph'', 21 August 2012</ref>\n* ''[[Look After Lulu!]]'' (1959), three-act farce adapted from [[Georges Feydeau]]\n* ''[[Waiting in the Wings (play)|Waiting in the Wings]]'' (1960), play in three acts\n* ''Suite in Three Keys: [[A Song at Twilight]]; Shadows of the Evening; [[Come Into the Garden, Maud (play)|Come Into the Garden, Maud]]'' (1966), a trilogy\n* ''Star Quality'' (1967), Coward's last play, comedy in three acts, fp Bath, 1985\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Revues, musicals, operetta and songs ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[London Calling!]]'' (1922, 1923), revue in collaboration with Ronald Jeans\n* ''[[On with the Dance (musical)|On with the Dance]]'' (1924, 1925), revue\n* ''[[This Year of Grace]]'' (1927, 1928), revue, originally ''[[Charles B. Cochran]]'s 1928 Revue''\n* ''[[Bitter Sweet]]'' (1928, 1929), operetta\n* ''[[Words and Music (musical)|Words and Music]]'' (1932), revue\n* ''[[Conversation Piece (musical)|Conversation Piece]]'' (1933), comedy with music\n* ''[[Operette (musical)|Operette]]'' (1937), musical play\n* ''[[Set to Music]]'' (1939), revue (a Broadway rewrite of ''Words and Music'')\n* ''[[Sigh No More (musical)|Sigh No More]]'' (1945), revue\n* ''[[Pacific 1860]]'' (1946), musical romance\n* ''[[Ace of Clubs (musical)|Ace of Clubs]]'' (1949), musical play\n* ''[[After the Ball (musical)|After the Ball]]'' (1953), musical based on ''[[Lady Windermere's Fan]]''\n* ''[[Sail Away (musical)|Sail Away]]'' (1959\u201361), musical comedy\n* ''[[The Girl Who Came to Supper]]'' (1963), musical comedy based on ''[[The Sleeping Prince (play)|The Sleeping Prince]]''\n* ''[[Oh, Coward!]]'' (1972) revue\n* ''[[Cowardy Custard]]'' (1972) revue\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Songs ===\nCoward wrote more than three hundred songs. The No\u00ebl Coward Society's website, drawing on performing statistics from the publishers and the [[PRS for Music|Performing Rights Society]], names \"[[Mad About the Boy]]\" (from ''Words and Music'') as Coward's most popular song, followed, in order, by:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* \"[[I'll See You Again]]\" (''Bitter Sweet'')\n* \"[[Mad Dogs and Englishmen (song)|Mad Dogs and Englishmen]]\" (''Words and Music'')\n* \"[[If Love Were All]]\" (''Bitter Sweet'')\n* \"Someday I'll Find You\" (''Private Lives'')\n* \"I'll Follow My Secret Heart\" (''Conversation Piece'')\n* \"[[London Pride (song)|London Pride]]\" (1941)\n* \"A Room With a View\" (''This Year of Grace'')\n* \"Mrs Worthington\" (1934)\n* \"Poor Little Rich Girl\" (''On with the Dance'')\n* \"The Stately Homes of England\" (''Operette'')\n{{div col end}}\n\nIn the society's second tier of favourites are:\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* \"The Party's Over Now\" (''Words and Music'')\n* \"Dearest Love\" (''Operette'')\n* \"Dear Little Caf\u00e9\" (''Bitter Sweet'')\n* \"Parisian Pierrot\" (''London Calling!'')\n* \"Men About Town\" (''Tonight at 8.30'')\n* \"Twentieth Century Blues\" (''Cavalcade'')\n* \"Uncle Harry\" (''Pacific 1860'')\n* \"[[Don't Let's Be Beastly to the Germans]]\" (1943)\n* \"There Are Bad Times Just Around the Corner\" (''Globe Review'')\n* \"Dance, Little Lady\" (''This Year of Grace'')\n* \"Has Anybody Seen Our Ship?\" (''Tonight at 8.30'')\n* \"[[I Went to a Marvellous Party]]\" (''Set to Music'')\n* \"Nina\" (''Sigh No More'')\n* \"A Bar on the Piccola Marina\" (1954)\n* \"Why Must the Show Go On?\" (''Together With Music'')\n* \"Sail Away\" (''Ace of Clubs'' and ''Sail Away'')\n* \"Zigeuner\" (''Bitter Sweet'')<ref name=ncsongs />\n{{div col end}}\n\nCoward was no fan of the works of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]],{{#tag:ref|\"I went to ''[[Iolanthe]]''... beautifully done and the music lovely but dated. It's no use, I ''hate'' Gilbert and Sullivan\".<ref>Day, p. 125</ref>|group= n}} but as a songwriter was nevertheless strongly influenced by them. He recalled: \"I was born into a generation that still took light music seriously. The lyrics and melodies of Gilbert and Sullivan were hummed and strummed into my consciousness at an early age. My father sang them, my mother played them{{space}}... my aunts and uncles, who were legion, sang them singly and in unison at the slightest provocation.\"<ref>Programme note for ''[[Cowardy Custard]]'' (1972) quoting ''The No\u00ebl Coward Song Book''</ref> His colleague Terence Rattigan wrote that as a lyricist Coward was \"the best of his kind since [[W. S. Gilbert]].\"<ref>Day, p. 257</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Adaptations of Coward works===\n*''[[The Queen Was in the Parlour (film)|The Queen Was in the Parlour]]'', directed by [[Graham Cutts]] (UK, 1927, based on [[The Queen Was in the Parlour|the play of the same name]])\n*''[[Easy Virtue (1928 film)|Easy Virtue]]'', directed by [[Alfred Hitchcock]] (UK, 1928, based on [[Easy Virtue (play)|the play of the same name]])\n*''[[The Vortex (film)|The Vortex]]'', directed by [[Adrian Brunel]] (UK, 1928, based on [[The Vortex|the play of the same name]])\n*''[[Private Lives (film)|Private Lives]]'', directed by [[Sidney Franklin (director)|Sidney Franklin]], [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] (1931, based on [[Private Lives|the play of the same name]])\n* ''[[Tonight Is Ours]]'', directed by [[Stuart Armstrong Walker|Stuart Walker]], [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] (1933, based on the play ''[[The Queen Was in the Parlour]]'')<!--January 21, 1933-->\n*''[[Cavalcade (1933 film)|Cavalcade]]'', directed by [[Frank Lloyd]], [[20th Century Fox]] (1933, based on [[Cavalcade (play)|the play of the same name]])<!--April 15, 1933-->\n*''[[Bitter Sweet (1933 film)|Bitter Sweet]]'', directed by [[Herbert Wilcox]] (UK, 1933, based on [[Bitter Sweet|the operetta of the same name]])<!--31 August 1933-->\n*''[[Design for Living (film)|Design for Living]]'', directed by [[Ernst Lubitsch]], Paramount (1933, based on [[Design for Living|the play of the same name]])<!--December 29, 1933-->\n*''[[The Terrible Lovers]]'', directed by [[Marc All\u00e9gret]] (France, 1936, based on the play ''[[Private Lives]]'')\n*''[[Bitter Sweet (1940 film)|Bitter Sweet]]'', directed by [[W. S. Van Dyke]], Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (1940, based on [[Bitter Sweet|the operetta of the same name]])\n*''[[We Were Dancing (film)|We Were Dancing]]'', directed by [[Robert Z. Leonard]], Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (1942, based on the plays ''[[We Were Dancing]]'', ''[[Ways and Means (play)|Ways and Means]]'' and ''[[Private Lives]]'')\n*''[[This Happy Breed (film)|This Happy Breed]]'', directed by [[David Lean]], [[Universal Pictures|Universal]] (UK, 1944, based on [[This Happy Breed|the play of the same name]]) (Coward was also a producer)\n*''[[Blithe Spirit (1945 film)|Blithe Spirit]]'', directed by [[David Lean]] (UK, 1945, based on [[Blithe Spirit (play)|the play of the same name]]) (Coward was also a producer)\n*''[[Brief Encounter]]'', directed by [[David Lean]] (UK, 1945, based on the play ''[[Still Life (play)|Still Life]]'') (Coward was also a screenwriter and producer)\n*''[[The Astonished Heart (film)|The Astonished Heart]]'', directed by [[Terence Fisher]] (UK, 1950, based on [[The Astonished Heart|the play of the same name]]) (Coward was also a screenwriter)\n*''[[Meet Me Tonight]]'', directed by [[Anthony Pelissier]] (UK, 1952, based on the plays ''[[Ways and Means (play)|Ways and Means]]'', ''[[Red Peppers]]'', and ''[[Fumed Oak]]'')\n*''[[Pretty Polly (film)|Pretty Polly]]'', directed by [[Guy Green (filmmaker)|Guy Green]] (UK, 1967, based on the short story ''Pretty Polly Barlow'')\n*''[[Brief Encounter (1974 film)|Brief Encounter]]'', directed by [[Alan Bridges]] (UK, 1974, based on the play ''[[Still Life (play)|Still Life]]'')\n* ''[[Relative Values (film)|Relative Values]]'', directed by Eric Styles (UK, 2000, based on [[Relative Values (play)|the play of the same name]])\n*''[[Easy Virtue (2008 film)|Easy Virtue]]'', directed by [[Stephan Elliott]] (UK, 2008, based on [[Easy Virtue (play)|the play of the same name]])<ref name=galeimdb>[http://infotrac.galegroup.com/galenet/wes_ttda?cause=http%3A%2F%2Fgalenet.galegroup.com%2Fservlet%2FGLD%2Fform%3FlocID%3Dwes_ttda%26l%3D2&cont=&sev=temp&type=session&sserv=no ''Contemporary Authors Online''], Thomson Gale, 2004, accessed 30 December 2008: requires subscription; and [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0002021/filmoyear Noel Coward] at the IMDB database, accessed 12 March 2009</ref>\n\n===Actor===\n*''[[Hearts of the World]]'' (1918) (uncredited)\n*''[[The Scoundrel (1935 film)|The Scoundrel]]'' (1935) as Anthony Mallare\n*''[[Men Are Not Gods]]'' (1936) (uncredited)\n*''[[In Which We Serve]]'' (1942) as Captain E.V. Kinross (also a screenwriter, producer and co-director)\n*''[[Blithe Spirit (1945 film)|Blithe Spirit]]'' (1945) (uncredited narrator) (also producer)\n*''[[Brief Encounter]]'' (1945) (uncredited narrator) (also a screenwriter and co-producer)\n*''[[The Astonished Heart (film)|The Astonished Heart]]'' (1950) as Dr. Christian Faber\n*''Blithe Spirit'' (1956 TV film) as Charles Condomine\n*''[[Around the World in 80 Days (1956 film)|Around the World in 80 Days]]'' (1956) as Roland Hesketh-Baggott\n*''[[Our Man in Havana (film)|Our Man in Havana]]'' (1959) as Hawthorne\n*''[[Surprise Package (film)|Surprise Package]]'' (1960) as King Pavel II\n*''[[Paris When It Sizzles]]'' (1964) as Alexander Meyerheim\n*''Ninety Years On'' (1964 TV film) as Narrator / Host\n*''[[Bunny Lake Is Missing]]'' (1965) as Horatio Wilson\n*''Androcles and the Lion'' (1967 TV film) as Caesar\n*''[[Boom! (film)|Boom!]]'' (1968) as The Witch of Capri\n*''[[The Italian Job]]'' (1969) as Mr. Bridger\n\n== Notes and references ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|group=n|colwidth=24em}}\n\n'''References'''\n{{Reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book |last = Barbey D'Aurevilly |first = Jules |others = George Walden (trans. and ed. of new edition) |year = 2002 |